{"title_page": "Group of death", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\nA '''group of death''' in a [[multi-stage tournament]] is a [[group tournament|group]] which is unusually competitive, because the number of strong competitors in the group is greater than the number of qualifying places available for the next phase of the tournament. Thus, in the group phase, one or more strong competitors in the \"group of death\" will necessarily be eliminated, who would otherwise have been expected to progress further in the tournament. The informal term was first used for groups in the [[FIFA World Cup]] finals. It is now also used in other [[association football]] tournaments and other sports.\n\nAfter the draw for a tournament has been made, debates often arise about which of the preliminary groups is \"the\" group of death.  This happens for multiple reasons: in part, from more general debates about the relative strengths of the various competitors; but, additionally, because there is no exact definition of the term \"group of death\".  Sometimes, the term simply signifies a group with only the strongest competitors, all of which are potential winners of the tournament, implying there is always precisely one such group; other definitions allow for multiple groups of death or for none at all.\n\nThe term is sometimes derided as a purely journalistic invention, a [[clich\u00e9]]<ref name=\"Limey\">{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/soccer/01/27/the.limey/index.html |title=Groups of death, Chop Suey and other soccer clich\u00e9s |last=Pickstone |first=Jon |author2=Ben Franklin |date=27 January 2006|work=The Limey  |publisher=SI.com|accessdate=4 December 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"ian-paul\">{{cite news |page=10 |title=Dutch can live in the Milan 'Group of Death' |first=Ian |last=Paul |work=The Herald |date=23 November 1992 |location=Glasgow |quote=If that notorious nickname of 1986, \"The Group of Death,\" which was used to describe Scotland's section in the World Cup finals in Mexico, was the child of an over-enthusiastic hack, three of the teams in Group B of the Champions' League would consider it a mild moniker for their section. }}</ref><ref name=\"Lovejoy\"/> or oversimplification based entirely on the unsportsmanlike notion that outcomes of such tournaments are largely predictable and that there are always [[Underdog (term)|underdog]]s, [[dark horse]]s and [[wikt:top dog|top dog]]s.<ref name=\"surprises\"/><ref name=\"Hawkey\">{{cite news |url=https://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2093-2209740,00.html |title=African dream lives in Ivory tower |last=Hawkey |first=Ian |date=4 June 2006 |work=The Sunday Times |accessdate=4 December 2009 |quote=The Group of Death has always been an ugly misnomer, although as every big tournament now seems obliged to identify its corpses early, the World Cup has to have one. }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Origin==\nThe term \"group of death\" was coined (as [[Spanish language|Spanish]] \"''grupo de la muerte''\") by Mexican journalists for [[1970 FIFA World Cup#Group 3|Group 3 of the 1970 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The beautiful team: in search of Pel\u00e9 and the 1970 Brazilians |first=Garry |last=Jenkins |author2=Pedro Redig |author3=Antonio Pires Soares  |year=1998 |isbn=0-684-81955-4 |page=22 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |quote=[[Jo\u00e3o Saldanha|Saldanha]] had no argument with the journalists who quickly christened the Group of Death.}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Motson |first=John |author2=Nick Brownlee |title=Motson's World Cup Extravaganza |publisher=Robson |year=2006 |page=171 |isbn=1-86105-936-1 |quote=Group of Death - The term 'Group of Death' was first coined by the Mexican press in 1970 to describe Group 3}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://mundial.emol.com/historia/1970.asp |title=M\u00e9xico 1970 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=[[El Mercurio]] Online |language=Spanish |year=2002 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=Se puede decir que el primer \"Grupo de la Muerte\" en la historia lo fue el 3 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091013080358/http://mundial.emol.com/historia/1970.asp |archivedate=13 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|year=1970 |title=Futbol |journal=Hispano Americano; semanario de la vida y la verdad |publisher=Tiempo |location=Mexico |volume=57 |pages=66, 103 |language=Spanish }}</ref> This featured [[1966 FIFA World Cup Final|reigning champions]] [[England national football team|England]], favourites and eventual champions [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], [[1962 FIFA World Cup Final|1962 runners-up]] [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] and [[Romania national football team|Romania]].\n\nIt was used again in Mexico for the [[1982 FIFA World Cup#Group C|second-phase Group C in the 1982 World Cup]] in Spain.<ref>{{cite journal|date=26 July 1982 |title=Mundial |journal=Razones |publisher=Decanova |language=Spanish |location=Mexico|issue=67|page=59 }}</ref> This grouped [[1978 FIFA World Cup Final|defending champions]] [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], the eventual champions [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and Brazil.<ref>\n{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/news/newsid=15443.html |title=Brazil: the unfinished samba |publisher=FIFA |work=Previous FIFA World Cups |date=26 July 2005 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=Only the top team in this group of death would qualify for the semi-finals. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111207001630/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/news/newsid%3D15443.html |archivedate=7 December 2011}}</ref> In 2007, ''[[The Guardian]]'' called this the deadliest-ever Group of Death.<ref name=\"knowledge\"/>\n\nIt was popularized after the draw for the [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986 World Cup]], when [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] manager [[Omar Borr\u00e1s]] so described [[Football World Cup 1986#Group E|Group E]], which included Uruguay, [[Germany national football team|West Germany]], [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]].<ref name=\"Lacey\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2004/jun/07/euro2004.sport136 |title=Dial D for death: Three previous winners in one group is a sign of the times |first=David |last=Lacey |date=7 June 2004 |work=[[The Guardian]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Robson landed with a flight of fancy; David Lacey on England's Concorde trip to Saudi Arabia for a friendly in the Gulf which stretches the credibility gap |first=David |last=Lacey |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=15 November 1988 |page=18 |quote=Omar Borras, who managed the Uruguayans in the 1986 World Cup, went into the tournament remarking that their first-round draw with West Germany, Scotland and Denmark was \"the group of death\"}}</ref> As with the 1970 group, this was the only one with all four teams from Europe and South America. The label was widely repeated by the English-language media.<ref name=\"upi19may\">{{cite news |title=World Cup Briefs |publisher=United Press International |date=19 May 1986 |quote=West Germany will play in Group F, dubbed ''The Group of Death'' because of the strength of its four teams. The others are Uruguay, Scotland team and Denmark.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=World Cup Roundup |first=Fred |last=Lief |publisher=United Press International |date=22 May 1986 |quote=Uruguay is part of the demanding Group E \u2014 known as the ''Group of Death'' \u2014 along with West Germany, Denmark and Scotland.}}</ref><ref name=\"norman-chad\">{{cite news |page=B4 |title=World's Eyes on Mexico: Month-Long Tournament Beginning May 31 Will Be Magnet for Hundreds of Million |first=Norman |last=Chad |work=Washington Post |date=25 May 1986 |quote=Group E, comprising Denmark, Scotland, West Germany and Uruguay, has been labeled the \"Group of Death\" because of the strength of the teams.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=H-1 |title=All the World Cup's a stage for soccer epic |first=Brian |last=Brown |work=San Diego Union-Tribune |date=1 June 1986 |quote=Group E (Queretaro, Nezahualcoyotl) This has come to be known as El Grupo de la Muerte (The Group of Death) because three of the top 10 teams are in it.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sports News |first=Fred |last=Lief |publisher=United Press International |date=14 June 1986 |quote=The game featured two teams from the ''Group of Death,'' so called because of the quality of the four squads. But the term assumed more sinister connotations as one tackle followed another.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sports News |first=Andrew |last=Warshaw |agency=Associated Press |date=24 June 1986 |quote=Then there was Alex Ferguson of Scotland, whose team had the misfortune of competing with Denmark, West Germany and Uruguay in what became known as the \"Group of Death.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Soccer: Nobody gets to be drawn until the fat guy sings - The Eternal City on the hopes, fears and ephemera surrounding this afternoon's World Cup lucky dip |first=David |last=Lacey |work=The Guardian |date=9 December 1999 |location=London |quote=The Scots would be extremely unlucky to get a 1990 equivalent of Mexico's 'Group of death' when they found themselves facing Uruguay, West Germany and Denmark.}}</ref> By the 1986 tournament rules, two or three of the four teams in each group would progress to the knockout phase; in the event, Scotland was the only team not to qualify from the prototypical \"group of death\". Uruguay were criticized for persistent foul play in the decisive match with Scotland; Borr\u00e1s was suspended for retorting, \"The Group of Death? Yes, there was a murderer on the field today. [[Jo\u00ebl Quiniou|The referee]].\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Gardner |first=Paul |title=The simplest game: the intelligent fan's guide to the world of soccer |publisher=Collier |year=1994 |edition=2nd |page=[https://archive.org/details/simplestgameinte00gard/page/96 96] |isbn=0-02-043225-9 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/simplestgameinte00gard/page/96 }}</ref>\n\n==Seedings==\nTournaments are often [[Seed (sports)|seeded]] to provide an even distribution of strong and weak competitors across all preliminary groups.<ref name=\"life2002f\">\n{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/dec/02/worldcupfootball2002.sport6 |title=It's the Group of Life |first=Paul |last=Wilson |work=The Observer |date=2 December 2001 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}\n</ref> However, in association football, [[:Category:Association football rankings|the ranking methods]] used for seeding may be crude. In the World Cup, until 2018 the usual strategy was for each group to contain one seeded team and three unseeded teams, with the unseeded teams picked from separate regional confederations.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mcwc/ip-201_10e-fwcdraw-history_52560.pdf |title=FIFA World Cup Draw History |publisher=FIFA }}\n</ref> Some [[CONCACAF|North American]], [[Confederation of African Football|African]] and [[Asian Football Confederation|Asian]] teams are significantly stronger than others.<ref name=\"Lacey\"/> The net result was that some groups may have had stronger teams than others.<ref name=\"Wagman\">{{cite web |url=http://www.soccertimes.com/wagman/2006/jun24.htm |title=FIFA must examine World Cup policies |last=Wagman |first=Robert |date=24 June 2006 |work=SoccerTimes |accessdate=4 December 2009 |location=Nuremberg |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091217071439/http://soccertimes.com/wagman/2006/jun24.htm |archive-date=17 December 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref> From the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 edition]] onwards this system has been changed, with a distribution of teams based on the [[FIFA World Rankings]] introduced, but with continental limitations still to be retained.\n\nThe reigning champion and the host nation or nations are traditionally among the seeds.<ref name=\"Wagman\"/> In the case of [[UEFA Euro 2008]], this meant three of the four seeds were among the weakest teams in the tournament: hosts [[Austria national football team|Austria]] and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], and surprise [[UEFA Euro 2004|2004 champions]] [[Greece national football team|Greece]]. [[2006 FIFA World Cup Final|2006 World Cup finalists]] [[France national football team|France]] and Italy were unseeded and ended up in [[UEFA Euro 2008 Group C|Group C]] with [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] and Romania.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/nov/30/newsstory.sport1 |title=Domenech fumes over potential Euro 2008 'group of death' |work=The Guardian |date=30 November 2007 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/dec/03/newsstory.sport7 |title=Domenech fury after France draw Italy in group of death |first=Kevin |last=McCarra |work=The Guardian |date=3 December 2007 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref> This was considered a \"group of death\" with Romania as underdogs against three of Europe's top sides.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/02122007/58/euro-2008-france-meet-italy-group-death.html |title=Euro 2008 - France to meet Italy in Group of Death |author=Reuters |work=Eurosport |date=2 December 2007 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=Romania are the unlucky team to be in Group C, the inevitable \"Group of Death\" |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213095750/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/02122007/58/euro-2008-france-meet-italy-group-death.html |archivedate=13 December 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/may/27/romania.euro2008 |title=Help us choose our Euro 2008 team |first=Lembit |last=Opik |work=The Guardian |date=27 May 2008 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote= We should back the underdog - Romania is in the group of death with France, Italy and the Netherlands, and they need all the help they can get.}}</ref>\n\nEven in competitions that give no seeding advantage to hosts or defending champions, \"group of death\" scenarios can still emerge. For example, the draw for the pools of the [[Rugby World Cup]] (union) primarily uses teams' positions in the [[World Rugby Rankings]] to determine placement in the \"pots\" for the draw. However, the draw has traditionally been held nearly three years before the competition. For example, the pool draw for the [[2015 Rugby World Cup]] was held in December 2012. This led to the host team, [[England national rugby union team|England]], being drawn into a pool that included traditional powers [[Australia national rugby union team|Australia]] and [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]], with only two teams able to advance to the knockout stage. Because Wales had gone winless in their [[2012 end-of-year rugby union internationals|November 2012 Tests]], they had dropped to ninth in the rankings at the time of the draw. Australia were third and England fifth at the time, placing all three teams into separate pots. In August 2015, [[World Rugby]] CEO [[Brett Gosper]] told the [[Press Association]] that the body was seriously considering rescheduling the draw for future World Cups to be much closer in time to the competition.<ref name=\"2015 RWC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/rugby/story/_/id/13464085/rugby-world-cup-organisers-seek-change-avoid-pool-death-scenarios-year-england-wales-australia |title=Rugby World Cup bosses will try to avoid 'pool of death' scenarios |agency=Press Association |publisher=[[ESPN (UK)]] |date=19 August 2015 |accessdate=20 August 2015}}</ref> However, this change could not be implemented for the [[2019 Rugby World Cup]] mainly because of the potential for ticketing clashes with the [[2020 Summer Olympics]], since Japan will host both events.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/rugby/story/_/id/14040768/japan-juggling-2019-rugby-world-cup-2020-tokyo-olympic-games |title=How the 2020 Olympic Games will affect the 2019 Rugby World Cup |first=Rob |last=Bartlett |publisher=[[ESPN (UK)]] |date=3 November 2015 |accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Debates and definitions==\nIn the [[FIFA World Cup]] tournament proper, the [[UEFA European Championship]] and the [[UEFA Champions League]], each preliminary group has four teams, two of which qualify for the knockout phase. Some sources imply all four teams must be in contention for a \"group of death\";<ref name=\"Wagman\" /><ref name=\"SanJose\"/><ref name=\"Chapman\"/> others allow for three teams fighting for two places, with one underdog making up the numbers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/finaldraw/news/newsid=1142570.html |title=Who's afraid of the Group of Death? |date=2 December 2009 |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=4 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091205174903/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/finaldraw/news/newsid%3D1142570.html |archivedate=5 December 2009}}</ref> In the latter case, the term gains an additional facet from the expected \"death\" of the weak team: [[Ally McCoist]]<ref>\n{{cite news |page=42 |title=Scotland head home with heads held high Breath of fresh air in an event choked by fear |first=Jeff |last=Powell |work=Daily Mail |date=16 June 1992 |location=London |quote=We've jumped out of what they called the group of death in 1986 into the group of certain death.}}</ref> and the [[The Herald (Glasgow)|Glasgow ''Herald'']]<ref>{{cite news |title=Let's be brave and add a touch of arrogance to our challenge |page=8 |first=James |last=Traynor |work=The Herald |date=8 June 1992 |location=Glasgow |quote=It was said before Scotland's participation in the finals of the 1986 World Cup that, having been drawn with Denmark, Germany and Uruguay, they had been placed in the Group of Death, but this time it could be said they are in the Group of Certain Death.}}</ref> described [[UEFA Euro 1992 Group B|Euro 1992 Group B]] as the \"Group of Certain Death\" because Scotland were grouped with the Netherlands, Germany and the [[CIS national football team|CIS]].  More extreme still, Ian Paul suggested [[1992\u201393 UEFA Champions League#Group B|semi-final Group B of the 1992\u201393 UEFA Champions League]] was a \"group of death\" for three of the four teams, with [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] almost sure to top the group and reach the [[1993 European Cup Final|final]].<ref name=\"ian-paul\" /> (Milan did in fact win all six matches against [[IFK G\u00f6teborg]], [[FC Porto|Porto]] and [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]].)\n\nIn the case of UEFA qualifying tournaments, groups have deeper seeding and always feature some weaker teams. For example, [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying Group B|Qualifying Group B]] for Euro 2008 was dubbed the \"group of death\" in Scotland because Scotland were drawn against Italy, France and [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]], respectively champion, finalist, and quarter-finalist at the 2006 World Cup. The presence in the group of [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]], [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]] and the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]] did not contribute to the label.<ref name=\"Limey\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jan/28/newsstory.sport12 |title=Smith rues fall-out of Scotland slump in group of death |first=Dominic |last=Fifield |work=The Guardian |date=28 January 2006  |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=a tough Euro 2008 qualifying group which will see his side face France, Italy and Ukraine }}</ref>\n\nIt is often assumed that a tournament has precisely one Group of Death.<ref>{{cite book |last=Leigh |first=John |author2=David Woodhouse |title=Football Lexicon |publisher=[[Faber and Faber]] |location=London |year=2006 |edition=revised |page=90 |isbn=0-571-23052-0 |quote='''Group of Death:''' A regular visitor to the language of football, this nice piece of hyperbole appears whenever World Cup draws are held, but can make an intermediate appearance at European Championships or other regional tournaments too. It is so familiar that commentators promptly debate which of the groups drawn might be ''the Group of Death'', as though it were a title which has to be assigned to one of them}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://goal.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/06/04/euro-2008-the-group-of-death/?pagemode=print |title=Euro 2008: The Group of Death |last=Bell |first=Jack |date=4 June 2008 |series=Goal blog|work=New York Times|accessdate=4 December 2009 |quote=Every soccer tournament has one }}</ref><ref name=\"Reyna\">{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D07E2DD1F31F931A15755C0A9609C8B63 |title=Simple Math for U.S.: Victory Is Only Option |last=Vecsey |first=George |date=22 June 2006 |work=New York Times |accessdate=4 December 2009 |quote=Reyna ... has maintained all along that the Americans were drawn into this year's Group of Death at the World Cup, even though Argentina and the Netherlands were drawn together in a different group. And the tangled results in the United States' group seem only to prove his point. ... The group is the only one of the eight four-team clusters to have all four teams in contention entering the final games. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9802E1D91131F933A25751C1A9639C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2 |title= Sports of The Times; With Field Fleshed Out, Now the Blood Starts to Boil |last=Vecsey |first=George |date=10 December 2005 |work=New York Times |accessdate=4 December 2009 |quote=By definition, every World Cup draw must have a Group of Death, a phrase translated into virtually every language \u2013 the Todesgruppe, they were calling it around here.}}</ref> In the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994 World Cup]], [[1994 FIFA World Cup#Group E|Group E]] (Italy, the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]], [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] and [[Norway national football team|Norway]]) was often given the label;<ref name=\"Lovejoy\">{{cite news |page=32 |title=Republic miss comfort zone; Germany's easy group ride makes them clear favourites |first=Joe |last=Lovejoy |work=The Independent |date=21 December 1993 |location=London |quote=American television, leaving no cliche unturned, promptly christened it ''the group of death''. }}</ref><ref name=\"surprises\">{{cite news |page=8C|title=Mix of talent, tactics make for most intriguing quartet |first=John |last=Harrell |work=USA Today |date=16 June 1994 |quote=Many refer to Group E at this summer's World Cup as the \"Group of Death.\" It's the strongest by far of the six four-team alignments, and at least one well-regarded team thus will not advance to the second round. The characterization might be a bit harsh. Perhaps the \"Group of Surprises\" is a better term. }}</ref><ref name=\"SanJose\">{{cite news |page=6F |title=Tie with Italy gives Mexico top spot in 'group of death'; tying Norway, Charlton's Ireland team also advances  |work=Mercury News |date=29 June 1994 |location=San Jose |quote=Group E was the \"Group of Death,\" a group with no weaklings, a group in which any of the four teams could, on a given day, beat any other.}}</ref><ref name=\"Chapman\">{{cite news |page=3B |title=Ireland will play short-handed in key match against Norway |first=Doug |last=Chapman |work=Journal-Bulletin |date=28 June 1994 |location=Providence |quote=Group E - dubbed the \"Group of Death\" because of its top-to-bottom competitiveness }}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news |page=18 |title=Battle of the Titans; Brazil, Italy Still Tower Over Rest of the World |first=Mike |last=Mulligan |author2=Diether Endlicher |work=Sun-Times |date=17 July 1994 |location=Chicago |quote=The draw with Mexico left the Italians in third place in the so-called Group of Death. }}</ref><ref name=\"Haydon\">\n{{cite news |page=C8 |title=First-round games full of goals and upsets |first=John |last=Haydon |work=Washington Times |date=3 July 1994 |location=Washington |quote=Group E, otherwise known as the \"Group of Death,\" lived up to its name. All four teams in the group - Mexico, Ireland, Italy and Norway - had a 1-1-1 record and four points each. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=1 |title=Jackie's Heroes march to glory; Republic goes wild over World Cup success |first=Suzanne |last=O'Shea |work=Daily Mail |date=29 June 1994 |location=London |quote=Group E, dubbed the 'group of death' because of the high calibre of its teams.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=B10 |title=Death on the World Cup Express |first=Lawrie |last=Mifflin |work=New York Times |date=28 June 1994 |location=New York |quote=the traditional nickname, \"Group of Death\" }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=D14 |title=Mexico tops Ireland; Group E deadlocked All four teams have 3 points in 'Group of Death' |first=Scott M. |last=Reid |work=Journal and Constitution |date=25 June 1994 |location=Atlanta |quote=The danger of Group E was recognized as soon as it was announced at the tournament draw last December. Italy, Ireland, Norway and Mexico were immediately dubbed members of \"The Group of Death.\" The name stuck. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=1C |title=Uff da: Norway on quite a roll |first=Patrick |last=Reusse |work=Star Tribune |date=20 June 1994 |location=Minneapolis |quote=There are six first-round groups in the World Cup tournament. It has been a tournament tradition to look at the assignments and to refer to one of the six as the \"Group of Death.\" }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=C7 |title=U.S. tops Mexico before 91,123 |first=George |last=Alfano |work=Press Enterprise |date=5 June 1994 |location=Riverside |quote=Mexico will play in the World Cup's Group E, which includes Italy, Ireland and Norway and is known as the \"Group of Death\" because three teams are ranked among the top 15 in the world. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=C2 |title=Here's World Cup team groupings |first=Joe |last=Luxbacher |work=Post-Gazette |date=17 April 1994  |location=Pittsburgh |quote=Group E: Italy, Ireland, Norway, Mexico. Probably the toughest group. Some analysts already are calling it the ''group of death,'' as all four teams are capable of advancing to the later rounds. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=D-1 |title=Fiesta expected tonight for soccer doubleheader |first=Mark |last=Ziegler |work=Union-Tribune |date=19 January 1994 |location=San Diego |quote=Some are calling it the \"Group of Death,\" if only because at most three of the four can advance to the second round. Meaning: At least one of them won't. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |publisher=United Press International |title=Group E: 'Group of Death' |first=Jeff |last=Shane |date=20 December 1993 |quote=Already, it's being labeled the ''Group of Death.'' Group E contains three of the top 10 teams in the current world ratings \u2013 No. 2 Italy, No. 4 Norway and No. 10 Ireland. Meanwhile, Mexico won the CONCACAF Gold Cup over the summer and made a very good showing at the Copa America. }}</ref> Brazil head coach [[Carlos Alberto Parreira]] said it was [[1994 FIFA World Cup#Group B|Group B]] (Brazil, [[Russia national football team|Russia]], [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] and [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]]);<ref>{{cite news |publisher=Xinhua |title=Brazil drawn in a 'group of death', says coach Parreira |date=19 December 1993 |location=Las Vegas |quote=Brazil were drawn in the world cup group which coach Carlos Alberto Parreira called 'the group of death'. Brazil plays Russia, Cameroon and Sweden in Group B.\" }}</ref> some reporters suggested both were \"groups of death\".<ref>{{cite news |page=35 |title=Cup draw cruel for top guns |author=AAP |work=Courier-Mail |date=21 December 1993 |quote=There is always one \"group of death\" in soccer's World Cups. In the US next year there may be two. making Brazil's Group B and Italy's Group E potentially the toughest. }}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news |title=Cup 'groups of death' |agency=Associated Press |work=Herald Sun |date=21 December 1993 |quote=TWO \"groups of death\" emerged from the Nevada desert in yesterday's soccer World Cup draw. [...] The draw made Brazil's Group B and Italy's Group E the toughest. }}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, after the draw for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup finals]], some commentators said there was no group of death.<ref name=\"bbc2010draw\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/8391833.stm |title=World Cup draw & reaction as it happened  |last=Stevenson |first=Jonathan |date=4 December 2009 |work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC |accessdate=13 December 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc2010draw\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://goal.com/en/news/1863/world-cup-2010/2009/12/04/1665698/world-cup-2010-exclusive-gavin-hunt-bemoans-tough-draw-for-south-|title=Gavin Hunt Bemoans 'Tough' Draw For South Africa |last=Pedroncelli |first=Peter |author2=Clyde Tlou |work=Goal.com |accessdate=13 December 2009 |quote=He believes that there is no Group of Death but singled out Group G as a major battlefield.}}</ref> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' said [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group G|Group G]] was the group of death because it had two of the top five nations in the [[FIFA World Rankings]], Brazil and [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], as well as the second-ranked African team, [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]]; it described fourth team [[Korea DPR national football team|North Korea]] as \"unenviable underdog\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/multimedia/photo_gallery/0912/soccer.world.cup.groups.of.death/content.1.html|title=2010: Group G: Brazil/North Korea/Ivory Coast/Portugal|work=Groups of Death in World Cup History|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=26 June 2010}}</ref> On the other hand, Andrew Downie of the ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'' said, \"No self-respecting Group of Death would be caught dead with North Korea in it... As far as I'm concerned, there is no Group of Death in this World Cup.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Africa/Africa-Monitor/2010/0615/World-Cup-How-can-the-Group-of-Death-include-North-Korea|title=How can the Group of Death include North Korea?|last=Downie|first=Andrew|date=15 June 2010|work=Christian Science Monitor|accessdate=26 June 2010}}</ref> Spain manager [[Vicente del Bosque]] said of [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group B|2014 World Cup Group B]], \"We have to define it as complicated but I don't believe this is the Group of Death. There are others very hard. But our group is difficult.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/world/news-display/spain-not-in--group-of-death--insists-del-bosque/80114 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216084623/http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/world/news-display/spain-not-in--group-of-death--insists-del-bosque/80114 |archivedate=16 December 2013 |title=Spain not in 'Group of Death', insists Del Bosque |publisher=[[Football Federation Australia]] |date=7 December 2013 |accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe \"Group of Death\" may simply be the one with the strongest teams, or the most strong teams.<ref name=\"surprises\"/><ref name=\"upi19may\"/><ref name=\"norman-chad\"/> Using FIFA World Rankings as a measure of the strength of the teams, ''[[The Guardian]]'' calculated in 2007 that the strongest \"Group of Death\" was [[UEFA Euro 1996 Group C|Euro 1996 Group C]]. The teams (and world rankings) were Germany (2), Russia (3), Italy (7) and the Czech Republic (10).<ref name=\"knowledge\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/dec/12/theknowledge.sport |title=The Knowledge: the deadliest group of death ever |first=John |last=Ashdown |author2=Alan Gardner |author3=James Dart  |work=The Guardian |date=12 December 2007 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Lacey\"/><ref name=\"easygroup\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/dec/11/sport.worldcup20062 |title=An easy group? Draw your own conclusions |first=Paul |last=Wilson |work=The Observer |date=11 December 2005 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref> This record was exceeded by the May 2012 rankings for [[UEFA Euro 2012 Group B|Euro 2012 Group B]], with Germany (2), the Netherlands (4), Portugal (5) and Denmark (10),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/jun/06/success-club-country-without-league-title|title=The Knowledge: Euro 2012 special, part one|last=Steinberg|first=Jacob|date=6 June 2012|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> but not the June rankings immediately before the tournament (3, 4, 10 and 9 respectively)<ref name=\"Associated Press\">{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/story/_/id/8015433/top-10-fifa-rankings-shaken-united-states-moves-28th |title=Spain still No. 1 in FIFA rankings |agency=Associated Press |publisher=ESPN.com |date=6 June 2012 |accessdate=8 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608073245/http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/story/_/id/8015433/top-10-fifa-rankings-shaken-united-states-moves-28th |archivedate=8 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"uk.eurosport.yahoo.com\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/video/03122011/58/euro-2012-group-b-bosses-react-group-death.html |title=Euro 2012 Group B: Bosses react to 'Group of Death' - Yahoo! Eurosport UK |publisher=Uk.eurosport.yahoo.com |accessdate=23 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120408232702/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/video/03122011/58/euro-2012-group-b-bosses-react-group-death.html |archivedate=8 April 2012}}</ref> In [[Women's association football|women's football]], [[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup#Group B|2007 World Cup Group B]] featured three of the top five teams in the [[FIFA Women's World Rankings]] entering the tournament \u2013&nbsp;the [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]] (1), [[Sweden women's national football team|Sweden]] (3) and [[North Korea women's national football team|North Korea]] (5) \u2013 with [[Nigeria women's national football team|Nigeria]] (24) being the \"minnows\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/worldcup/2007-09-11-us-game-1_N.htm |title=USA's group tied in knots after World Cup openers |first=Sal |last=Ruibal |newspaper=USA Today |date=12 September 2007 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |quote=At the 2007 FIFA Women's World Cup, they call Group B the Group of Death because its quartet of high-ranked and unpredictable teams are capable of defeating any opponent. . . . But after Tuesday's pair of gloomy, rain-drenched opening ties [i.e. [[Tie (draw)|draw]]s], Group B has suddenly become sudden death.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/print?id=424508&type=story |title=U.S. women face Group of Death scenario again |first=Graham |last=Hays |publisher=ESPNsoccernet |date=23 April 2007 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525153029/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/print?id=424508&type=story |archivedate=25 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nThere may be an emphasis on the \"group of death\" having a tight finish, with all four teams in contention.<ref name=\"Reyna\"/> This was the case in [[1990 FIFA World Cup#Group F|Group F of the 1990 World Cup]], in which five of the six matches were drawn,<ref>{{cite news |title=Speculation not for Robson |first=Stuart |last=Jones |work=The Times |date=14 June 1990 |location=Cagliari |quote=The Group of Death, as the Italians call the World Cup group confined to the islands of Sardinia and Sicily, promises to come to the most dramatic conclusion of the first round. The four teams are inseparable and, whatever the results this weekend, the permutations cannot be fully unravelled until the closing fixtures on June 21. }}</ref> and in [[1994 FIFA World Cup#Group E|Group E of the 1994 World Cup]], when all four teams finished level on points and [[goal difference]].<ref name=\"Haydon\"/>\n\nHowever, the label is usually applied in anticipation of the tournament rather than in retrospect.<ref name=\"Hawkey\"/> Simon Burnton comments, \"Inevitably, one of the big teams involved gets so scared about being in the Group of Death that they play really badly, meaning not only that they go home in disappointment and disgrace, but that the group turns out not to be so very troublesome after all.\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2009/mar/21/burnton-saturday-column |title=Forget Death \u2013 what about a Group of Poop? |first=Simon |last=Burnton |work=The Guardian |date=21 March 2009 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref> David Lacey said, \"Draws may nominate a group of death but results decide its real mortality rating.  France and Argentina found this out in Japan.\"<ref name=\"Lacey\"/> Lacey also said, \"There are groups of death and groups of death wishes. In Euro 2000 [[UEFA Euro 2000#Group D|Group D]] looked daunting but was shrugged aside by the Netherlands, the co-hosts, and France, the eventual champions, with the Czechs, runners-up in 1996, and the Danes, winners in 1992, offering scant resistance. [[UEFA Euro 2000#Group A|Group A]] turned out to be the killer.\"\n\nLack of consensus about which is the group of death can fuel debates among fans and journalists.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/jun/19/match.sport |title=Milosevic breathes life into the group of death |page=A5 |first=Roy |last=Collins |work=The Guardian |date=19 June 2000  |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=People love talking about groups of death at European Championships, World Cups and even the Champions League.}}</ref> In the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]], ''The Guardian'' called [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group F|Group F]] (Sweden, England, Argentina and [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]]) \"the group of death\"<ref name=\"Lacey\"/><ref name=\"life2002\">{{cite news |url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/worldcup2002/countries/page/0,,719107,00.html |title=World Cup 2002: Russia's group |work=The Guardian |date=2 December 2001 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=Compared to England's group of death, this [sc. [[2002 FIFA World Cup - Group H|Group H]]] is a group of life. }}</ref> and [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group E|Group E]] (Germany, the Republic of Ireland, Cameroon and [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]]) \"the other Group of Death\".<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=26 May 2002 |page=8 (Sport) |title=Best bets: stick with France and ignore the buzz |author=\"Mr Prospector\" }}</ref> South Koreans called [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group D|Group D]] ([[South Korea national football team|South Korea]], [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]], Portugal and [[Poland national football team|Poland]]) the \"Real Group of Death\".<ref>\n{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/jun/11/worldcupfootball2002.sport2 |title=Korea get attack of the jitters after Friedel frustrates |first=Jon |last=Brodkin |work=The Guardian |pages=D10\u201311 |date=11 June 2002 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref> In the 2006 World Cup, both [[2006 FIFA World Cup Group C|Group C]] (Argentina, the Netherlands, Ivory Coast and [[Serbia and Montenegro national football team|Serbia and Montenegro]])<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jun/10/worldcup2006.sport18 |title=Kezman's inside knowledge of Holland may see Serbs strike fatal blow in Group of Death |first=Michael |last=Walker |work=The Guardian |date=10 June 2006 |location=Leipzig |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=No World Cup is complete without either a Group of Death or a sticker album, and Group C delivers both items }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/dec/10/newsstory.sport6 |title=Argentina join the Dutch in group of death |first=Paul |last=Kelso |work=The Guardian |date=10 December 2005 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}\n</ref> and [[2006 FIFA World Cup Group E|Group E]] (Italy, [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]], Czech Republic and the United States)<ref name=\"easygroup\"/> were nominated as \"group of death\".<ref name=\"Reyna\"/> In the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]], three groups were acknowledged in the media as \"group of death\": [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group B|Group B]] (Spain, the Netherlands, [[Chile national football team|Chile]], [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]]),<ref name=\"Jackson\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/dec/06/world-cup-2014-draw-group-death-spain |title=World Cup 2014 draw: Spain and Holland in 'group of death' |first=Jamie |last=Jackson |work=The Guardian |date=6 December 2013 |accessdate=6 December 2013 }}</ref> [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group D|Group D]] ([[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]], England and [[Italy national football team|Italy]]),<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/dec/06/world-cup-2014-england-group-death-brazil |title=World Cup 2014: England to kick off 'group of death' in the jungle |first=Owen |last=Gibson |work=The Guardian |date=6 December 2013 |accessdate=6 December 2013 }}</ref> and [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group G|Group G]] (Germany, Portugal, Ghana and the United States);<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/worldcup/2013/12/06/2014-world-cup-usa-draw-group-of-death-ghana-portugal-germany/3892009/ |title=U.S. drawn into World Cup 'Group of Death': Ghana, Portugal, Germany |work=USA Today |date=6 December 2013 |accessdate=6 December 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://prosoccertalk.nbcsports.com/2013/12/06/world-cup-2014-groups-of-death-from-deadly-to-deadliest/ |title=World Cup 2014 Groups of Death: From Deadly to Deadliest |first=Nicholas |last=Mendola |work=NBC Sports |date=6 December 2013 |accessdate=6 December 2013 }}</ref> Group G was considered especially difficult in the U.S., as they had been eliminated by its \"weakest\" team, Ghana, in each of the past two tournaments. In the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]], there were three groups that were considered groups of death: [[2018 FIFA World Cup Group E|Group E]] ([[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]], [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]] and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]), [[2018 FIFA World Cup Group F|Group F]] ([[2014 FIFA World Cup Final|reigning champions]] [[Germany national football team|Germany]], [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] and [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]]) and [[2018 FIFA World Cup Group D|Group D]] ([[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]], [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] and [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/world-cup-groups-of-death-over-the-years-which-teams-should/1k6od8ho35kas15rgajikwn5no|title=World Cup 'Groups of Death' over the years & which teams should be afraid in Russia 2018 {{!}} Goal.com|access-date=2018-08-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League group stage]], Group H ([[Real Madrid]], [[Tottenham Hotspur]], [[Borussia Dortmund]] and [[APOEL]]) and in the [[2019\u201320 UEFA Champions League group stage]], Group F ([[SK Slavia Prague]],[[Inter Milan]],[[Borussia Dortmund]],and [[FC Barcelona|FC Barcelona,]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/08/29/football/champions-league-draw-barcelona-liverpool-spt-intl/index.html|title=Barcelona drawn in Champions League 'group of death'|first=Matias |last=Grez|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>) was considered \"the group of death\".\n\nIn the 1998-99 UEFA Champions League group stage there were six group which all of them contained four teams, but only the group winners and the two second-placed teams with the best records would qualify for the next round. In that season, Group C (Holders Real Madrid, 1998 UEFA Cup Winners Internazionale, 1998 UEFA Cup semi-finalists Spartak Moscow and comparative minoows Sturm Graz) and Group D (Spanish champions Barcelona, former Champions Cup winners Bayern Munich and Manchester United as well as relative minnows Br\u00f8ndby) could well be considered group of deaths. In the event, those groups were the two whose second-placed teams would go on to have the best records among second-placed teams, and the top two teams of Group D, Bayern Munich and Manchester United, would actually go on to contest the final (ironically in the stadium of the \"big\" eliminated team of the group, the Camp Nou where FC Barcelona play.\n\nFans may describe as the \"group of death\" any tough group which contains their favoured team. [[George Vecsey]] says, \"In soccer, every nation always thinks it has been stiffed into the toughest pool, the Group of Death.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C04E6DD113CF935A2575BC0A9619C8B63 |title=An American in the World Cup Is Dreaming Big |last=Vecsey |first=George |date=16 August 2007|work=New York Times |accessdate=4 December 2009}}</ref> In this sense, David Warren comments that a \"top seeding in a finals group gives a country a good chance to advance and the best chance to avoid a so-called group of death\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://goal.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/09/10/the-road-to-south-africa/ |title=Road to South Africa |last=Warren |first=David |date=10 September 2009 |series=Goal blog|work=New York Times|accessdate=4 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Other sports==\nThe label \"group of death\" has been used in other sports than association football; for example:\n;[[Basketball]]: [[1994 FIBA World Championship#Group A|1994 FIBA World Championship Group A]];<ref>{{cite news |publisher=Agence France Presse |title=World Championship |date=2 August 1994 |quote=China was 17th at Barcelona and slotted in what coach Jiang Xingquan calls the group of death, against three teams China has never bested. }}</ref> [[2010 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament#Midwest Regional \u2013 St. Louis, Missouri|2010 NCAA Men's Midwest Regional]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/discussion/2010/03/08/DI2010030803202.html  |title=Tiger Woods at the Masters return, NCAA Tournament, NBA and more |last=Wilbon |first=Michael |authorlink=Michael Wilbon |date=16 March 2010 |series=The Chat House with Michael Wilbon |work=Washington Post|quote=Georgetown and Maryland, of course, is in that Group of Death Midwest region where you've got Tennessee, Ohio State, Oklahoma State, Michigan State, a totally known but damn good Iowa State team. Why the NCAA Tournament would stack the region where the overall No. 1 is I don't know |accessdate=27 March 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tri-cityherald.com/2010/03/17/941727/a-fair-bit-of-chalk-ending-in.html |title=My chalky bracket ends in Jayhawk |last=Degerman |first=Eric |date=17 March 2010 |work=Rub of the Green |publisher=Tri-City Herald |quote=the Midwest bracket, dubbed \"The Group of Death\" by those who follow World Cup soccer |accessdate=27 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229162617/http://www.tri-cityherald.com/2010/03/17/941727/a-fair-bit-of-chalk-ending-in.html |archivedate=29 February 2012}}</ref> [[2014 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament#Midwest Regional \u2013 Indianapolis, Indiana|2014 NCAA Men's Midwest Regional]] (where undefeated Wichita State was pitted in an early round against a young, talented Kentucky team playing far better than their ranking would suggest, and in a bracket which also included powerhouses Michigan, Duke and Louisville);<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/collegebasketballnation/post/_/id/96336/bracket-winners-and-losers-2 |title=Bracket winners and losers |work=Men's College Basketball Blog |first=Andy |last=Katz |authorlink=Andy Katz |publisher=[[ESPN.com]] |quote=The [[2013\u201314 Wichita State Shockers men's basketball team|Shockers]] did earn a No. 1 seed with an undefeated season. But they were given the \"Group of Death\" bracket with No. 8 [[2013\u201314 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team|Kentucky]] (if it gets past [[2013\u201314 Kansas State Wildcats men's basketball team|Kansas State]]), No. 4 [[2013\u201314 Louisville Cardinals men's basketball team|Louisville]], No. 3 [[2013\u201314 Duke Blue Devils men's basketball team|Duke]] and No. 2 [[2013\u201314 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|Michigan]]. Wow. |date=16 March 2014 |accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref> [[2016 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament#East Regional \u2013 Philadelphia, PA|2016 NCAA Men's East Regional]];<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/16-things-to-know-about-the-ncaa-east-region--plus-who-wins-170126104.html |title=16 things to know about the NCAA East Region, plus who wins |first=Pat |last=Forde |authorlink=Pat Forde |work=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |quote=Toughest of the four [regions]. Three teams won a major-conference title. Five teams are in the [[Ken Pomeroy|Pomeroy]] Ratings top 15. This is your group of death. |date=14 March 2016 |accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> [[2019 FIBA Basketball World Cup#Group H|2019 FIBA World Cup Group H]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ca.nba.com/news/fiba-basketball-world-cup-2019-canada-draw-group-of-death-with-australia-lithuania-senegal/sq2duek0iypj1k1iu36ubo1dv|title=FIBA Basketball World Cup 2019: Canada draws 'group of death' with Australia, Lithuania, Senegal|last=Gay|first=Carlan|date=16 March 2019|website=NBA.com|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n;[[Rugby union]]: [[1995 Rugby World Cup#Pool B|1995 World Cup Pool B]];<ref name=\"carling\">{{cite news |title=In Brief |work=Herald Sun |date=22 May 1995 |location=Australia |quote=Carling insists that England's pool is \"the group of death\", rather than the section containing Australia, South Africa, Canada and Romania which already has been given that lurid tag }}</ref> [[2001\u201302 Heineken Cup#Pool 6|2001\u201302 Heineken Cup Pool 6]];<ref>{{cite news |page=A21 |title=Falcons' fatal blow in Group of Death |first=Bryn |last=Palmer |work=The Guardian |date=1 October 2001 }}</ref> [[2003 Rugby World Cup#Group A|2003 World Cup Group A]];<ref>{{cite news |p=32 |title=A man born to take centre stage |first=Brian |last=O'Driscoll |work=The Guardian |date=7 October 2003 |quote=[Ireland] are in the so-called Group of Death with Argentina and the host nation. }}</ref> [[2011\u201312 Heineken Cup#Pool 3|2011-12 Heineken Cup Pool 3]] ([[Glasgow Warriors]] were drawn against reigning champions [[Leinster Rugby|Leinster]], a young [[Bath Rugby|Bath]] side and the best of the lowest-seeded teams [[Montpellier H\u00e9rault Rugby|Montpellier]]); [[2007 Rugby World Cup - Pool D|2007 World Cup Pool D]];<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2007/sep/02/comment.comment1 |title=Let the beauty of rugby shine out in France |first=Alan |last=Ruddock |work=The Observer |date=2 September 2007 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=If Ireland is in the inevitable group of death alongside France and Argentina, then England's is the group of attrition}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2007/sep/06/guardianextra11.guardianspecial921 |title=Is this Ireland's moment? |first1=Michael |last1=Cheika |authorlink1=Michael Cheika |first2=Jason |last2=Leonard |authorlink2=Jason Leonard |work=The Guardian |date=7 September 2007 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref> [[2011 Rugby World Cup Pool B]]; [[2015 Rugby World Cup Pool A]] (where Australia, hosts England and Wales were placed in the same group, being second, third and fourth respectively in the World Rugby rankings as of 21 September 2015<ref>http://www.worldrugby.org/rankings</ref>); [[2019 Rugby World Cup Pool C]]\n;[[Paralympic association football]]: [[Football 7-a-side at the 2012 Summer Paralympics#Group B|2012 Summer Paralympics 7-a-side Group B]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympic-sport/9290076/London-2012-Paralympics-Great-Britain-seven-a-side-footballers-drawn-in-Group-of-Death-at-Games.html|title=London 2012 Paralympics: Great Britain seven-a-side footballers drawn in 'Group of Death' at Games|access-date=2016-09-12}}</ref> [[Football 7-a-side at the 2016 Summer Paralympics#Group A|2016 Summer Paralympics 7-a-side Group A]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/soccer/little-cheer-for-irelands-paralympic-seven-a-side-team-at-home-of-football-420148.html|title=Little cheer for Ireland's Paralympic seven-a-side team at home of football|access-date=2016-09-12}}</ref> [[Football 5-a-side at the 2016 Summer Paralympics#Group B|2016 Summer Paralympics 5-a-side Group B]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/news/football-5-a-side-will-be-tight-but-can-anyone-beat-triple-paralympic-champions-brazil |title=Football 5-a-side will be tight, but can anyone beat triple Paralympic champions Brazil? |website=Rio 2016 |access-date=2016-09-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922202352/https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/news/football-5-a-side-will-be-tight-but-can-anyone-beat-triple-paralympic-champions-brazil |archivedate=22 September 2016}}</ref> \n;[[Rugby league]]: [[1995 Rugby League World Cup#Group 3|1995 World Cup Group 3]];<ref>{{cite news |page=65 |title=Death or Glory! |first=Jonathan |last=Davies |work=Sunday Mirror |date=8 October 1995 |quote=Wales tackle France in our opening fixture in what has chillingly been dubbed the Group of Death. }}</ref> [[2008 Rugby League World Cup#Group A|2008 World Cup Group A]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/sep/28/rugbyleagueworldcup2008.rugbyleague |title=The briefing: The Rugby League World Cup, 25 October - 22 November |first=R |last=W |work=The Observer |date=28 September 2008  |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote='A' is the group of death - Australia, New Zealand, England and Papua New Guinea }}</ref> (the 2008 group was deliberately constructed by putting the top four seeds in one group, with three to qualify, to ensure more competitive matches in the first phase, and guarantee weaker sides a semi-final place)\n;[[Cricket]]: [[2008 Twenty20 Cup North Division]];<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/2299392/Lancashires-Steven-Croft-has-perfect-timing.html |title=Lancashire's Steven Croft has perfect timing |last=Collomosse |first=Andrew |date=5 May 2008|work=Daily Telegraph |accessdate=4 December 2009|location=Old Trafford }}</ref> [[2009 ICC World Twenty20#Group C|2009 World Twenty20 Group C]];,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/twenty20/5430945/World-Twenty20-Super-Eights-guide-West-Indies.html |title=World Twenty20 Super Eights guide: West Indies |last=Collins |first=Nick Published |date=10 June 2009|work=Daily Telegraph |accessdate=4 December 2009 |quote=Having survived the \"group of death\" in the opening round, the West Indies find themselves in a similar position at the super eight stage}}</ref> [[2012 ICC World Twenty20#Super8 - Group 2|2012 World Twenty20 Super8 - Group 2]]\n;[[Ice hockey]]: [[Ice hockey at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's qualification#Group G|2010 Olympic men's qualifying group G]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://slapshot.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/02/07/european-puck-germany-to-the-2010-olympics/ |title=European Puck: Germany to the 2010 Olympics |last=Klein |first=Jeff Z. |date=7 February 2009|series=Slap shot blog|work=New York Times|accessdate=4 December 2009 |quote=Meanwhile in Group G at Oslo \u2013 the hotly contested \"Group of Death\"}}</ref>\n\n==Variants==\n\n===Variant definitions===\n\"Group of death\" has occasionally been used to characterise a qualifying group in some other way. The southern section preliminary round Group 5 of the 1990-91 [[Football League Trophy|Leyland DAF Cup]] had lowly teams replaying poorly-attended matches;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/jeremy.hicks/flt/flt9091.html |title=Leyland DAF Cup - 1990/91 |first=Jeremy |last=Hicks |work=The Football League Trophy |accessdate=3 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226234154/http://homepage.ntlworld.com/jeremy.hicks/flt/flt9091.html |archivedate=26 February 2009}}</ref> after many postponements, Robert Pryce commented: \"The Leyland Daf Cup Southern Section preliminary round's Group of Death has achieved almost total rigor mortis.\"<ref>{{cite news |page=20 |title=Soccer Diary |first=Robert |last=Pryce |work=The Guardian |date=12 January 1991 |location=London }}</ref>\n\nScotland manager [[Andy Roxburgh]] described [[UEFA Euro 1992 qualifying Group 2|Euro 1992 qualifying Group 2]] as a \"group of death\" in a different sense because of the lack of a glamorous opponent \"to get people out of the house and into [[Hampden Park]].\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Roxburgh sure of delivery - Group Two: Scotland v San Marino |first=Patrick |last=Glenn |work=The Guardian |date=13 November 1991 |location=London |quote=I called this the group of death because there wasn't a big country to brighten it, to capture the imagination, to get people out of the house and into Hampden Park. Romania and Bulgaria have outstanding talents but they are not a draw. The Swiss are the same, emergent and improving, but not attractive. A France, an Italy, a Germany, even an England in our case, was needed to lift the thing. But we have one last chore and the Scotland team I wanted is here.}}</ref> The group combined [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]], [[Romania national football team|Romania]], [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]], [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]], and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]].\n\nThe [[1994 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)#Final round|Asian final qualifying group for the 1994 World Cup]] featured two sets of militantly hostile neighbours: Iran, Iraq, and Saudi Arabia; and North Korea, South Korea, and Japan. This was called the \"group of death\" for [[black humour]].<ref>\n{{cite journal |title=Saudi soccer success in Qatar |first=Phil |last=Minshull |work=The Middle East |page=40 |issue=N229 |issn=0305-0734 |date=1 December 1993 |location=Saudi Arabia |quote=Western commentators dubbed the 13-day tournament in Qatar the \"Group of Death\" since fate had brought together six potentially volatile elements.}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news |page=78 |title=The mother of all wars and the father of all football matches? Let's wait and see |first=Alan |last=Fraser |work=Daily Mail |date=22 October 1993 |location=London |quote=The Iraq and Iran footballers have been breakfasting together, chatting even, part of a bizarre logistical cocktail in which the so-called 'group of death' - also including Saudi Arabia, North and South Korea and Japan - have been billeted in the same hotel. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Social Studies |first=Michael |last=Kesterton |work=The Globe and Mail |date=21 October 1993 |location=Canada |quote=The six have been nicknamed the Group of Death, writes Mark Skipworth in The Sunday Times of London. Three of the six - Iran, Iraq and Saudi Arabia - have recently been at war and two others - North and South Korea - have never officially ended their state of conflict. (The sixth team is from Japan.) }}</ref>\n\nA similar quip was made of the [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)#Group 1|UEFA qualifying group 1 for the 1998 World Cup]]:\n{{cquote|The toughest group in the World Cup qualifying competition is the Group of Death. For the 1998 qualifiers, group one takes the title with ease. Bosnia, Croatia and Slovenia were drawn in group one. . . .  There was, mercifully, no Serb-dominated rump Yugoslavia drawn in the same group. But there was, as far as the others are concerned, the next worse thing: the Greeks. They share the Orthodox religion with the Serbs, and give them strong diplomatic support. Pity Denmark, the reigning European champions, who make up the group.<ref>{{cite news |page=1 |title=It's War: World Cup squares up for the battle of the Balkans |first=John |last=Mullin |work=The Guardian |date=13 December 1995 }}</ref>}}\n\n===Related terms===\nOccasionally, alternatives to \"group of death\" are proffered. [[Javier Clemente]] said of [[1998 FIFA World Cup - Group D|1998 World Cup Group D]], \"This is not the group of death, as some people have said. It is the group of heart attacks\"<ref>{{cite news |page=A5 |title=Clemente's hopes may go up in puff of smoke |work=The Guardian |date=24 June 1998 }}</ref> John Harrell said of [[1994 FIFA World Cup#Group E|1994 World Cup Group E]], \"The characterization might be a bit harsh. Perhaps the 'Group of Surprises' is a better term.\"<ref name=\"surprises\"/>\n\nSometimes the excitement of a close contest between high-quality teams has suggested the positive \"group of life\" is more appropriate than \"group of death\".<ref>\n{{cite news|url=http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2006/06/23/story6677.asp |title=Sudden death in group of life |work=Irish Examiner |date=23 June 2006 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=what had turned out to be the World Cup\u2019s Group of Life. The supporters of all four competing nations would have woken up in various cities in Germany yesterday morning with dreams of further glory in their minds. }}{{dead link|date=March 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Of [[2002 FIFA World Cup - Group F|2002 World Cup Group F]], Paul Wilson said, \"England's group is not so much the group of death as the group of life, for few others promise any drama\"<ref name=\"life2002f\"/> Of [[2006 FIFA World Cup Group C|2006 World Cup Group C]], [[Gary Lineker]] said after Argentina's demolition of Serbia and Montenegro, \"Argentina produced one of the great performances in recent World Cup history. The group of death has become the group of life.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/5057832.stm |title=Argentina 6-0 Serbia & Montenegro |work=BBC Sport |date=16 June 2006 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref>\n\nHowever, \"Group of Life\" has also been used as the opposite of \"Group of Death\", to mean an easy group with weak teams: examples include [[2002 FIFA World Cup#Group H|2002 World Cup Group H]];<ref name=\"life2002f\"/><ref>\n{{cite news |url=http://sport.scotsman.com/japansworldcup/Group-H-in-detail.2327985.jp |title=\nGroup H in detail |work=Scotland on Sunday  |date=19 May 2002 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=Tipped to make it through to the knockout stages in only their second World Cup thanks to a very favourable draw into the 'Group of Life' }}</ref> [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification - UEFA Group 6|2006 World Cup UEFA qualifying Group 6]];<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/james-lawton-rooneys-lurking-brilliance-fails-to-instil-hope-of-better-times-for-england-at-the-big-show-510692.html |title=Rooney's lurking brilliance fails to instil hope of better times for England at the Big Show |first=James |last=Lawton |work=The Independent |date=13 October 2005 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=a qualifying pool so benignly unthreatening it might have been known as the Group of Life }}</ref> [[2006 FIFA World Cup Group D|2006 World Cup Group D]];<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/worldcup2006/WORLD-CUP-PREVIEW-We-could.1556397.jp |title=We could be in for a Ruud awakening |first=Alan |last=Swann |work=Peterborough Today |date= June 2006 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=If Group C is the 'Group of Death' then this is the 'Group of Life' }}</ref> [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group C|2010 World Cup Group C]];<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/dec/04/england-world-cup-2010 |title=Lucky England secure place in 'group of life' in football 2010 World Cup draw |first=Paul |last=Hayward |work=[[The Guardian]] |date= 4 December 2009 |location=United Kingdom |accessdate=5 December 2009 |quote=Lucky England secure place in 'group of life' in football 2010 World Cup draw}}</ref> and [[2018 FIFA World Cup#Group A|2018 World Cup Group A]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://amp.businessinsider.com/russia-world-cup-draw-the-group-of-life-2017-12 |title=Charts show that Russia's World Cup group is unlike the others|first=Samantha |last=Lee |work=[[Business Insider]] |date= 2 December 2017 |location=United Kingdom |accessdate=10 June 2018 |quote=there is what some are calling the Group of Life and, coincidentally, it features the host nation, Russia. As for Russia's Group A, those four teams add up to a combined ranking of 180, 77 more than any other group.}}</ref> Chuck Culpepper wrote of [[2006 FIFA World Cup Group B|2006 World Cup Group B]], 'If each World Cup draw brings a \"Group of Death,\" anointed for its incomparable rigor among the eight groups, England 2006 surely occupies the Group of Life, or the Group of Tranquillity, or the Group of So Few Worries We Spent All Day Yesterday Following the [[Wayne Rooney#International career|Metatarsal Melodrama]] Rather Than Worry About [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]].'<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/jun/15/sports/sp-england15 |title=Getting the Group Rate on Life and Death |first=Chuck |last=Culpepper |work=LA Times |date=15 June 2006 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref> [[Radio T\u00e9l\u00e9vision Suisse]] said Switzerland was \"far from being in a group of 'death'\" when drawn in [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group E|2014 World Cup Group E]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rts.ch/sport/football/international/equipe-suisse/5434964-groupe-mi-figue-mi-raisin-pour-la-suisse-qui-retrouve-la-france.html |title=Groupe mi-figue mi-raisin pour la Suisse, qui retrouve la France |language=fr |publisher=Radio T\u00e9l\u00e9vision Suisse |date=6 December 2014 |accessdate=23 June 2014 |quote=La Suisse se retrouve, en effet, dans le groupe E qui est tr\u00e8s loin de s'apparenter \u00e0 un groupe de la \"mort\".}}</ref> Polish-speaking media tend to refer to relatively tough and forgiving groups as ''grupa \u015bmierci'' (\"group of death\") and ''grupa marze\u0144'' (\"dream group\") respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.przegladsportowy.pl/pilka-nozna/euro-2016,losowanie-grup-euro-2016-grupa-marzen-i-grupa-smierci,artykul,622356,1,12341.html |title=Jaka by\u0142aby grupa marze\u0144 i \u015bmierci Polak\u00f3w na Euro 2016 |publisher=Przegl\u0105d Sportowy |date=18 November 2015 |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref>{{original research inline|date=July 2016}}\n\n{{anchor|Sleep}}<!-- [[Group of sleep]] redirects here -->[[1986 FIFA World Cup#Group F|1986 World Cup Group F]], with two goals in the first four games combined, was dubbed the \"Group of Sleep\".<ref>\n{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/international/england/3017725/England-pay-for-past-failures.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130421124609/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/international/england/3017725/England-pay-for-past-failures.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=21 April 2013 |title=England pay for past failures |work=Daily Telegraph |date=28 November 2001 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=the Mexicans also gave a title to 1986's Group Six. England, Poland, Portugal and Morocco, the locals in Monterrey were fond of saying, was the 'Group of Sleep'. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/internationals/lisbon-evokes-mixture-of-memories-733305.html |title=Lisbon evokes mixture of memories |first=Tim |last=Rich |work=The Independent |date=24 June 2004 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=the dreadfully dull \"Group of Sleep\" }}</ref>\n\nBefore the [[UEFA Euro 2012]] tournament draw, financial writer Chris Sloley coined the term \"Group of Debt\" for a possible group comprising [[PIGS (economics)|PIIGS]] [[European debt crisis|indebted countries]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://citywire.co.uk/global/football-pundits-eye-potential-group-of-debt-at-euro-2012/a548683 |title=Football pundits eye potential \u2018Group of Debt\u2019 at Euro 2012 |first=Chris |last=Sloley |publisher=[[Citywire]] |date=2 December 2011 |accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref> in the event, three of these ([[Spain national football team|Spain]], [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]]) were grouped together with [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] in [[UEFA Euro 2012 Group C|Group C]], while [[Greece national football team|Greece]] and [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] were in other groups.\n\n\"Group of Champions\" has been used in the [[UEFA Champions League]] both for groups where all teams are former champions of that competition,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/30/sports/soccer/german-and-british-teams-grouped-together-in-champions-league.html|title=German and British Teams Grouped Together in Champions League|last=Das|first=Andrew|date=29 August 2013|work=The New York Times|quote=Barcelona is in what amounts to a Group of Champions with A.C. Milan, Ajax Amsterdam and Glasgow Celtic; those four clubs have combined for 16 European championships.|accessdate=12 July 2016}}; {{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/draw-centre/cup=1/season=2014/round=2000479/|title=UEFA Champions League-Group stage draw-Monaco|date=29 August 2013|publisher=[[UEFA]]|quote=Johan Cruyff on AFC Ajax, who will play AC Milan, FC Barcelona and Celtic FC in Group H: \"It\u2019s a fantastic thing for football that these clubs get drawn against other. It\u2019s another group of champions ...\"|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> and for groups where all teams are reigning domestic champions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/08/30/sport/football/football-champions-league-draw/|title=Group of champions pairs Manchester City and Real Madrid|date=30 August 2012|publisher=[[CNN]]|quote=The \"Group of Death\" contains all champions of their respective leagues with Dortmund claiming the Bundesliga title for the second straight year and Ajax winning the Dutch crown.|accessdate=12 July 2016}}; {{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2914/champions-league/2013/08/29/4223389/champions-league-draw-32-expert-verdicts|title=Champions League draw: The experts' verdict|date=29 August 2013|work=Goal.com|quote=It's not quite the Group of champions that was so disastrous last season|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.whoateallthepies.tv/miscellaneous/4271/the_top_10_foot.html |title=The top seven World Cup Groups of Death |work=Who ate all the Pies |orig-year=3 December 2007 |date=4 December 2009 |author=Ollie }}\n* {{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/columns/story?id=708444&cc=5739&ver=global |title=Five of the best Groups of Death |last=Adams |first=Tom |date=4 December 2009 |work=soccernet |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=4 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091207193353/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/columns/story?id=708444&cc=5739&ver=global |archivedate=7 December 2009}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/rssbest/groupsofdeath.html |publisher=[[RSSSF]] |title=Groups of death |work=The Best of Rec.Sport.Soccer  |date=3 March 2003 |accessdate=8 December 2009 |author=Ll\u00e9o |author2=Karel Stokkermans |author3=Michael Hynes |display-authors=etal}}\n* {{cite web |url=https://amp.businessinsider.com/russia-world-cup-draw-the-group-of-life-2017-12 |website=[[Business Insider]] |title=Charts show Russia's World Cup group is unlike the others |date=2 December 2017 |accessdate=10 June 2018 |author=Samantha Lee and Cork Gaines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Group of Death}}\n[[Category:Association football terminology]]\n[[Category:Rugby union terminology]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\nA '''group of death''' in a [[multi-stage tournament]] is a [[group tournament|group]] which is unusually competitive, because the number of strong competitors in the group is greater than the number of qualifying places available for the next phase of the tournament. Thus, in the group phase, one or more strong competitors in the \"group of death\" will necessarily be eliminated, who would otherwise have been expected to progress further in the tournament. The informal term was first used for groups in the [[FIFA World Cup]] finals. It is now also used in other [[association football]] tournaments and other sports.\n\nAfter the draw for a tournament has been made, debates often arise about which of the preliminary groups is \"the\" group of death.  This happens for multiple reasons: in part, from more general debates about the relative strengths of the various competitors; but, additionally, because there is no exact definition of the term \"group of death\".  Sometimes, the term simply signifies a group with only the strongest competitors, all of which are potential winners of the tournament, implying there is always precisely one such group; other definitions allow for multiple groups of death or for none at all.\n\nThe term is sometimes derided as a purely journalistic invention, a [[clich\u00e9]]<ref name=\"Limey\">{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/soccer/01/27/the.limey/index.html |title=Groups of death, Chop Suey and other soccer clich\u00e9s |last=Pickstone |first=Jon |author2=Ben Franklin |date=27 January 2006|work=The Limey  |publisher=SI.com|accessdate=4 December 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"ian-paul\">{{cite news |page=10 |title=Dutch can live in the Milan 'Group of Death' |first=Ian |last=Paul |work=The Herald |date=23 November 1992 |location=Glasgow |quote=If that notorious nickname of 1986, \"The Group of Death,\" which was used to describe Scotland's section in the World Cup finals in Mexico, was the child of an over-enthusiastic hack, three of the teams in Group B of the Champions' League would consider it a mild moniker for their section. }}</ref><ref name=\"Lovejoy\"/> or oversimplification based entirely on the unsportsmanlike notion that outcomes of such tournaments are largely predictable and that there are always [[Underdog (term)|underdog]]s, [[dark horse]]s and [[wikt:top dog|top dog]]s.<ref name=\"surprises\"/><ref name=\"Hawkey\">{{cite news |url=https://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2093-2209740,00.html |title=African dream lives in Ivory tower |last=Hawkey |first=Ian |date=4 June 2006 |work=The Sunday Times |accessdate=4 December 2009 |quote=The Group of Death has always been an ugly misnomer, although as every big tournament now seems obliged to identify its corpses early, the World Cup has to have one. }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Origin==\nThe term \"group of death\" was coined (as [[Spanish language|Spanish]] \"''grupo de la muerte''\") by Mexican journalists for [[1970 FIFA World Cup#Group 3|Group 3 of the 1970 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The beautiful team: in search of Pel\u00e9 and the 1970 Brazilians |first=Garry |last=Jenkins |author2=Pedro Redig |author3=Antonio Pires Soares  |year=1998 |isbn=0-684-81955-4 |page=22 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |quote=[[Jo\u00e3o Saldanha|Saldanha]] had no argument with the journalists who quickly christened the Group of Death.}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Motson |first=John |author2=Nick Brownlee |title=Motson's World Cup Extravaganza |publisher=Robson |year=2006 |page=171 |isbn=1-86105-936-1 |quote=Group of Death - The term 'Group of Death' was first coined by the Mexican press in 1970 to describe Group 3}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://mundial.emol.com/historia/1970.asp |title=M\u00e9xico 1970 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=[[El Mercurio]] Online |language=Spanish |year=2002 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=Se puede decir que el primer \"Grupo de la Muerte\" en la historia lo fue el 3 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091013080358/http://mundial.emol.com/historia/1970.asp |archivedate=13 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|year=1970 |title=Futbol |journal=Hispano Americano; semanario de la vida y la verdad |publisher=Tiempo |location=Mexico |volume=57 |pages=66, 103 |language=Spanish }}</ref> This featured [[1966 FIFA World Cup Final|reigning champions]] [[England national football team|England]], favourites and eventual champions [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], [[1962 FIFA World Cup Final|1962 runners-up]] [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] and [[Romania national football team|Romania]].\n\nIt was used again in Mexico for the [[1982 FIFA World Cup#Group C|second-phase Group C in the 1982 World Cup]] in Spain.<ref>{{cite journal|date=26 July 1982 |title=Mundial |journal=Razones |publisher=Decanova |language=Spanish |location=Mexico|issue=67|page=59 }}</ref> This grouped [[1978 FIFA World Cup Final|defending champions]] [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], the eventual champions [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and Brazil.<ref>\n{{cite news|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/news/newsid=15443.html |title=Brazil: the unfinished samba |publisher=FIFA |work=Previous FIFA World Cups |date=26 July 2005 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=Only the top team in this group of death would qualify for the semi-finals. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111207001630/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/news/newsid%3D15443.html |archivedate=7 December 2011}}</ref> In 2007, ''[[The Guardian]]'' called this the deadliest-ever Group of Death.<ref name=\"knowledge\"/>\n\nIt was popularized after the draw for the [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986 World Cup]], when [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] manager [[Omar Borr\u00e1s]] so described [[Football World Cup 1986#Group E|Group E]], which included Uruguay, [[Germany national football team|West Germany]], [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]].<ref name=\"Lacey\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2004/jun/07/euro2004.sport136 |title=Dial D for death: Three previous winners in one group is a sign of the times |first=David |last=Lacey |date=7 June 2004 |work=[[The Guardian]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Robson landed with a flight of fancy; David Lacey on England's Concorde trip to Saudi Arabia for a friendly in the Gulf which stretches the credibility gap |first=David |last=Lacey |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=15 November 1988 |page=18 |quote=Omar Borras, who managed the Uruguayans in the 1986 World Cup, went into the tournament remarking that their first-round draw with West Germany, Scotland and Denmark was \"the group of death\"}}</ref> As with the 1970 group, this was the only one with all four teams from Europe and South America. The label was widely repeated by the English-language media.<ref name=\"upi19may\">{{cite news |title=World Cup Briefs |publisher=United Press International |date=19 May 1986 |quote=West Germany will play in Group F, dubbed ''The Group of Death'' because of the strength of its four teams. The others are Uruguay, Scotland team and Denmark.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=World Cup Roundup |first=Fred |last=Lief |publisher=United Press International |date=22 May 1986 |quote=Uruguay is part of the demanding Group E \u2014 known as the ''Group of Death'' \u2014 along with West Germany, Denmark and Scotland.}}</ref><ref name=\"norman-chad\">{{cite news |page=B4 |title=World's Eyes on Mexico: Month-Long Tournament Beginning May 31 Will Be Magnet for Hundreds of Million |first=Norman |last=Chad |work=Washington Post |date=25 May 1986 |quote=Group E, comprising Denmark, Scotland, West Germany and Uruguay, has been labeled the \"Group of Death\" because of the strength of the teams.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=H-1 |title=All the World Cup's a stage for soccer epic |first=Brian |last=Brown |work=San Diego Union-Tribune |date=1 June 1986 |quote=Group E (Queretaro, Nezahualcoyotl) This has come to be known as El Grupo de la Muerte (The Group of Death) because three of the top 10 teams are in it.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sports News |first=Fred |last=Lief |publisher=United Press International |date=14 June 1986 |quote=The game featured two teams from the ''Group of Death,'' so called because of the quality of the four squads. But the term assumed more sinister connotations as one tackle followed another.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sports News |first=Andrew |last=Warshaw |agency=Associated Press |date=24 June 1986 |quote=Then there was Alex Ferguson of Scotland, whose team had the misfortune of competing with Denmark, West Germany and Uruguay in what became known as the \"Group of Death.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Soccer: Nobody gets to be drawn until the fat guy sings - The Eternal City on the hopes, fears and ephemera surrounding this afternoon's World Cup lucky dip |first=David |last=Lacey |work=The Guardian |date=9 December 1999 |location=London |quote=The Scots would be extremely unlucky to get a 1990 equivalent of Mexico's 'Group of death' when they found themselves facing Uruguay, West Germany and Denmark.}}</ref> By the 1986 tournament rules, two or three of the four teams in each group would progress to the knockout phase; in the event, Scotland was the only team not to qualify from the prototypical \"group of death\". Uruguay were criticized for persistent foul play in the decisive match with Scotland; Borr\u00e1s was suspended for retorting, \"The Group of Death? Yes, there was a murderer on the field today. [[Jo\u00ebl Quiniou|The referee]].\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Gardner |first=Paul |title=The simplest game: the intelligent fan's guide to the world of soccer |publisher=Collier |year=1994 |edition=2nd |page=[https://archive.org/details/simplestgameinte00gard/page/96 96] |isbn=0-02-043225-9 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/simplestgameinte00gard/page/96 }}</ref>\n\n==Seedings==\nTournaments are often [[Seed (sports)|seeded]] to provide an even distribution of strong and weak competitors across all preliminary groups.<ref name=\"life2002f\">\n{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2001/dec/02/worldcupfootball2002.sport6 |title=It's the Group of Life |first=Paul |last=Wilson |work=The Observer |date=2 December 2001 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}\n</ref> However, in association football, [[:Category:Association football rankings|the ranking methods]] used for seeding may be crude. In the World Cup, until 2018 the usual strategy was for each group to contain one seeded team and three unseeded teams, with the unseeded teams picked from separate regional confederations.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/mcwc/ip-201_10e-fwcdraw-history_52560.pdf |title=FIFA World Cup Draw History |publisher=FIFA }}\n</ref> Some [[CONCACAF|North American]], [[Confederation of African Football|African]] and [[Asian Football Confederation|Asian]] teams are significantly stronger than others.<ref name=\"Lacey\"/> The net result was that some groups may have had stronger teams than others.<ref name=\"Wagman\">{{cite web |url=http://www.soccertimes.com/wagman/2006/jun24.htm |title=FIFA must examine World Cup policies |last=Wagman |first=Robert |date=24 June 2006 |work=SoccerTimes |accessdate=4 December 2009 |location=Nuremberg |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091217071439/http://soccertimes.com/wagman/2006/jun24.htm |archive-date=17 December 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref> From the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 edition]] onwards this system has been changed, with a distribution of teams based on the [[FIFA World Rankings]] introduced, but with continental limitations still to be retained.\n\nThe reigning champion and the host nation or nations are traditionally among the seeds.<ref name=\"Wagman\"/> In the case of [[UEFA Euro 2008]], this meant three of the four seeds were among the weakest teams in the tournament: hosts [[Austria national football team|Austria]] and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], and surprise [[UEFA Euro 2004|2004 champions]] [[Greece national football team|Greece]]. [[2006 FIFA World Cup Final|2006 World Cup finalists]] [[France national football team|France]] and Italy were unseeded and ended up in [[UEFA Euro 2008 Group C|Group C]] with [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] and Romania.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/nov/30/newsstory.sport1 |title=Domenech fumes over potential Euro 2008 'group of death' |work=The Guardian |date=30 November 2007 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/dec/03/newsstory.sport7 |title=Domenech fury after France draw Italy in group of death |first=Kevin |last=McCarra |work=The Guardian |date=3 December 2007 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref> This was considered a \"group of death\" with Romania as underdogs against three of Europe's top sides.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/02122007/58/euro-2008-france-meet-italy-group-death.html |title=Euro 2008 - France to meet Italy in Group of Death |author=Reuters |work=Eurosport |date=2 December 2007 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=Romania are the unlucky team to be in Group C, the inevitable \"Group of Death\" |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213095750/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/02122007/58/euro-2008-france-meet-italy-group-death.html |archivedate=13 December 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/may/27/romania.euro2008 |title=Help us choose our Euro 2008 team |first=Lembit |last=Opik |work=The Guardian |date=27 May 2008 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote= We should back the underdog - Romania is in the group of death with France, Italy and the Netherlands, and they need all the help they can get.}}</ref>\n\nEven in competitions that give no seeding advantage to hosts or defending champions, \"group of death\" scenarios can still emerge. For example, the draw for the pools of the [[Rugby World Cup]] (union) primarily uses teams' positions in the [[World Rugby Rankings]] to determine placement in the \"pots\" for the draw. However, the draw has traditionally been held nearly three years before the competition. For example, the pool draw for the [[2015 Rugby World Cup]] was held in December 2012. This led to the host team, [[England national rugby union team|England]], being drawn into a pool that included traditional powers [[Australia national rugby union team|Australia]] and [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]], with only two teams able to advance to the knockout stage. Because Wales had gone winless in their [[2012 end-of-year rugby union internationals|November 2012 Tests]], they had dropped to ninth in the rankings at the time of the draw. Australia were third and England fifth at the time, placing all three teams into separate pots. In August 2015, [[World Rugby]] CEO [[Brett Gosper]] told the [[Press Association]] that the body was seriously considering rescheduling the draw for future World Cups to be much closer in time to the competition.<ref name=\"2015 RWC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/rugby/story/_/id/13464085/rugby-world-cup-organisers-seek-change-avoid-pool-death-scenarios-year-england-wales-australia |title=Rugby World Cup bosses will try to avoid 'pool of death' scenarios |agency=Press Association |publisher=[[ESPN (UK)]] |date=19 August 2015 |accessdate=20 August 2015}}</ref> However, this change could not be implemented for the [[2019 Rugby World Cup]] mainly because of the potential for ticketing clashes with the [[2020 Summer Olympics]], since Japan will host both events.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/rugby/story/_/id/14040768/japan-juggling-2019-rugby-world-cup-2020-tokyo-olympic-games |title=How the 2020 Olympic Games will affect the 2019 Rugby World Cup |first=Rob |last=Bartlett |publisher=[[ESPN (UK)]] |date=3 November 2015 |accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Debates and definitions==\nIn the [[FIFA World Cup]] tournament proper, the [[UEFA European Championship]] and the [[UEFA Champions League]], each preliminary group has four teams, two of which qualify for the knockout phase. Some sources imply all four teams must be in contention for a \"group of death\";<ref name=\"Wagman\" /><ref name=\"SanJose\"/><ref name=\"Chapman\"/> others allow for three teams fighting for two places, with one underdog making up the numbers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/finaldraw/news/newsid=1142570.html |title=Who's afraid of the Group of Death? |date=2 December 2009 |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=4 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091205174903/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/finaldraw/news/newsid%3D1142570.html |archivedate=5 December 2009}}</ref> In the latter case, the term gains an additional facet from the expected \"death\" of the weak team: [[Ally McCoist]]<ref>\n{{cite news |page=42 |title=Scotland head home with heads held high Breath of fresh air in an event choked by fear |first=Jeff |last=Powell |work=Daily Mail |date=16 June 1992 |location=London |quote=We've jumped out of what they called the group of death in 1986 into the group of certain death.}}</ref> and the [[The Herald (Glasgow)|Glasgow ''Herald'']]<ref>{{cite news |title=Let's be brave and add a touch of arrogance to our challenge |page=8 |first=James |last=Traynor |work=The Herald |date=8 June 1992 |location=Glasgow |quote=It was said before Scotland's participation in the finals of the 1986 World Cup that, having been drawn with Denmark, Germany and Uruguay, they had been placed in the Group of Death, but this time it could be said they are in the Group of Certain Death.}}</ref> described [[UEFA Euro 1992 Group B|Euro 1992 Group B]] as the \"Group of Certain Death\" because Scotland were grouped with the Netherlands, Germany and the [[CIS national football team|CIS]].  More extreme still, Ian Paul suggested [[1992\u201393 UEFA Champions League#Group B|semi-final Group B of the 1992\u201393 UEFA Champions League]] was a \"group of death\" for three of the four teams, with [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] almost sure to top the group and reach the [[1993 European Cup Final|final]].<ref name=\"ian-paul\" /> (Milan did in fact win all six matches against [[IFK G\u00f6teborg]], [[FC Porto|Porto]] and [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]].)\n\nIn the case of UEFA qualifying tournaments, groups have deeper seeding and always feature some weaker teams. For example, [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying Group B|Qualifying Group B]] for Euro 2008 was dubbed the \"group of death\" in Scotland because Scotland were drawn against Italy, France and [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]], respectively champion, finalist, and quarter-finalist at the 2006 World Cup. The presence in the group of [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]], [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]] and the [[Faroe Islands national football team|Faroe Islands]] did not contribute to the label.<ref name=\"Limey\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jan/28/newsstory.sport12 |title=Smith rues fall-out of Scotland slump in group of death |first=Dominic |last=Fifield |work=The Guardian |date=28 January 2006  |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=a tough Euro 2008 qualifying group which will see his side face France, Italy and Ukraine }}</ref>\n\nIt is often assumed that a tournament has precisely one Group of Death.<ref>{{cite book |last=Leigh |first=John |author2=David Woodhouse |title=Football Lexicon |publisher=[[Faber and Faber]] |location=London |year=2006 |edition=revised |page=90 |isbn=0-571-23052-0 |quote='''Group of Death:''' A regular visitor to the language of football, this nice piece of hyperbole appears whenever World Cup draws are held, but can make an intermediate appearance at European Championships or other regional tournaments too. It is so familiar that commentators promptly debate which of the groups drawn might be ''the Group of Death'', as though it were a title which has to be assigned to one of them}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://goal.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/06/04/euro-2008-the-group-of-death/?pagemode=print |title=Euro 2008: The Group of Death |last=Bell |first=Jack |date=4 June 2008 |series=Goal blog|work=New York Times|accessdate=4 December 2009 |quote=Every soccer tournament has one }}</ref><ref name=\"Reyna\">{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D07E2DD1F31F931A15755C0A9609C8B63 |title=Simple Math for U.S.: Victory Is Only Option |last=Vecsey |first=George |date=22 June 2006 |work=New York Times |accessdate=4 December 2009 |quote=Reyna ... has maintained all along that the Americans were drawn into this year's Group of Death at the World Cup, even though Argentina and the Netherlands were drawn together in a different group. And the tangled results in the United States' group seem only to prove his point. ... The group is the only one of the eight four-team clusters to have all four teams in contention entering the final games. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9802E1D91131F933A25751C1A9639C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=2 |title= Sports of The Times; With Field Fleshed Out, Now the Blood Starts to Boil |last=Vecsey |first=George |date=10 December 2005 |work=New York Times |accessdate=4 December 2009 |quote=By definition, every World Cup draw must have a Group of Death, a phrase translated into virtually every language \u2013 the Todesgruppe, they were calling it around here.}}</ref> In the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994 World Cup]], [[1994 FIFA World Cup#Group E|Group E]] (Italy, the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]], [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] and [[Norway national football team|Norway]]) was often given the label;<ref name=\"Lovejoy\">{{cite news |page=32 |title=Republic miss comfort zone; Germany's easy group ride makes them clear favourites |first=Joe |last=Lovejoy |work=The Independent |date=21 December 1993 |location=London |quote=American television, leaving no cliche unturned, promptly christened it ''the group of death''. }}</ref><ref name=\"surprises\">{{cite news |page=8C|title=Mix of talent, tactics make for most intriguing quartet |first=John |last=Harrell |work=USA Today |date=16 June 1994 |quote=Many refer to Group E at this summer's World Cup as the \"Group of Death.\" It's the strongest by far of the six four-team alignments, and at least one well-regarded team thus will not advance to the second round. The characterization might be a bit harsh. Perhaps the \"Group of Surprises\" is a better term. }}</ref><ref name=\"SanJose\">{{cite news |page=6F |title=Tie with Italy gives Mexico top spot in 'group of death'; tying Norway, Charlton's Ireland team also advances  |work=Mercury News |date=29 June 1994 |location=San Jose |quote=Group E was the \"Group of Death,\" a group with no weaklings, a group in which any of the four teams could, on a given day, beat any other.}}</ref><ref name=\"Chapman\">{{cite news |page=3B |title=Ireland will play short-handed in key match against Norway |first=Doug |last=Chapman |work=Journal-Bulletin |date=28 June 1994 |location=Providence |quote=Group E - dubbed the \"Group of Death\" because of its top-to-bottom competitiveness }}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news |page=18 |title=Battle of the Titans; Brazil, Italy Still Tower Over Rest of the World |first=Mike |last=Mulligan |author2=Diether Endlicher |work=Sun-Times |date=17 July 1994 |location=Chicago |quote=The draw with Mexico left the Italians in third place in the so-called Group of Death. }}</ref><ref name=\"Haydon\">\n{{cite news |page=C8 |title=First-round games full of goals and upsets |first=John |last=Haydon |work=Washington Times |date=3 July 1994 |location=Washington |quote=Group E, otherwise known as the \"Group of Death,\" lived up to its name. All four teams in the group - Mexico, Ireland, Italy and Norway - had a 1-1-1 record and four points each. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=1 |title=Jackie's Heroes march to glory; Republic goes wild over World Cup success |first=Suzanne |last=O'Shea |work=Daily Mail |date=29 June 1994 |location=London |quote=Group E, dubbed the 'group of death' because of the high calibre of its teams.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=B10 |title=Death on the World Cup Express |first=Lawrie |last=Mifflin |work=New York Times |date=28 June 1994 |location=New York |quote=the traditional nickname, \"Group of Death\" }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=D14 |title=Mexico tops Ireland; Group E deadlocked All four teams have 3 points in 'Group of Death' |first=Scott M. |last=Reid |work=Journal and Constitution |date=25 June 1994 |location=Atlanta |quote=The danger of Group E was recognized as soon as it was announced at the tournament draw last December. Italy, Ireland, Norway and Mexico were immediately dubbed members of \"The Group of Death.\" The name stuck. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=1C |title=Uff da: Norway on quite a roll |first=Patrick |last=Reusse |work=Star Tribune |date=20 June 1994 |location=Minneapolis |quote=There are six first-round groups in the World Cup tournament. It has been a tournament tradition to look at the assignments and to refer to one of the six as the \"Group of Death.\" }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=C7 |title=U.S. tops Mexico before 91,123 |first=George |last=Alfano |work=Press Enterprise |date=5 June 1994 |location=Riverside |quote=Mexico will play in the World Cup's Group E, which includes Italy, Ireland and Norway and is known as the \"Group of Death\" because three teams are ranked among the top 15 in the world. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=C2 |title=Here's World Cup team groupings |first=Joe |last=Luxbacher |work=Post-Gazette |date=17 April 1994  |location=Pittsburgh |quote=Group E: Italy, Ireland, Norway, Mexico. Probably the toughest group. Some analysts already are calling it the ''group of death,'' as all four teams are capable of advancing to the later rounds. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |page=D-1 |title=Fiesta expected tonight for soccer doubleheader |first=Mark |last=Ziegler |work=Union-Tribune |date=19 January 1994 |location=San Diego |quote=Some are calling it the \"Group of Death,\" if only because at most three of the four can advance to the second round. Meaning: At least one of them won't. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |publisher=United Press International |title=Group E: 'Group of Death' |first=Jeff |last=Shane |date=20 December 1993 |quote=Already, it's being labeled the ''Group of Death.'' Group E contains three of the top 10 teams in the current world ratings \u2013 No. 2 Italy, No. 4 Norway and No. 10 Ireland. Meanwhile, Mexico won the CONCACAF Gold Cup over the summer and made a very good showing at the Copa America. }}</ref> Brazil head coach [[Carlos Alberto Parreira]] said it was [[1994 FIFA World Cup#Group B|Group B]] (Brazil, [[Russia national football team|Russia]], [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] and [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]]);<ref>{{cite news |publisher=Xinhua |title=Brazil drawn in a 'group of death', says coach Parreira |date=19 December 1993 |location=Las Vegas |quote=Brazil were drawn in the world cup group which coach Carlos Alberto Parreira called 'the group of death'. Brazil plays Russia, Cameroon and Sweden in Group B.\" }}</ref> some reporters suggested both were \"groups of death\".<ref>{{cite news |page=35 |title=Cup draw cruel for top guns |author=AAP |work=Courier-Mail |date=21 December 1993 |quote=There is always one \"group of death\" in soccer's World Cups. In the US next year there may be two. making Brazil's Group B and Italy's Group E potentially the toughest. }}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news |title=Cup 'groups of death' |agency=Associated Press |work=Herald Sun |date=21 December 1993 |quote=TWO \"groups of death\" emerged from the Nevada desert in yesterday's soccer World Cup draw. [...] The draw made Brazil's Group B and Italy's Group E the toughest. }}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, after the draw for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup finals]], some commentators said there was no group of death.<ref name=\"bbc2010draw\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/8391833.stm |title=World Cup draw & reaction as it happened  |last=Stevenson |first=Jonathan |date=4 December 2009 |work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC |accessdate=13 December 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc2010draw\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://goal.com/en/news/1863/world-cup-2010/2009/12/04/1665698/world-cup-2010-exclusive-gavin-hunt-bemoans-tough-draw-for-south-|title=Gavin Hunt Bemoans 'Tough' Draw For South Africa |last=Pedroncelli |first=Peter |author2=Clyde Tlou |work=Goal.com |accessdate=13 December 2009 |quote=He believes that there is no Group of Death but singled out Group G as a major battlefield.}}</ref> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' said [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group G|Group G]] was the group of death because it had two of the top five nations in the [[FIFA World Rankings]], Brazil and [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], as well as the second-ranked African team, [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]]; it described fourth team [[Korea DPR national football team|North Korea]] as \"unenviable underdog\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/multimedia/photo_gallery/0912/soccer.world.cup.groups.of.death/content.1.html|title=2010: Group G: Brazil/North Korea/Ivory Coast/Portugal|work=Groups of Death in World Cup History|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=26 June 2010}}</ref> On the other hand, Andrew Downie of the ''[[Christian Science Monitor]]'' said, \"No self-respecting Group of Death would be caught dead with North Korea in it... As far as I'm concerned, there is no Group of Death in this World Cup.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Africa/Africa-Monitor/2010/0615/World-Cup-How-can-the-Group-of-Death-include-North-Korea|title=How can the Group of Death include North Korea?|last=Downie|first=Andrew|date=15 June 2010|work=Christian Science Monitor|accessdate=26 June 2010}}</ref> Spain manager [[Vicente del Bosque]] said of [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group B|2014 World Cup Group B]], \"We have to define it as complicated but I don't believe this is the Group of Death. There are others very hard. But our group is difficult.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/world/news-display/spain-not-in--group-of-death--insists-del-bosque/80114 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216084623/http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/world/news-display/spain-not-in--group-of-death--insists-del-bosque/80114 |archivedate=16 December 2013 |title=Spain not in 'Group of Death', insists Del Bosque |publisher=[[Football Federation Australia]] |date=7 December 2013 |accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe \"Group of Death\" may simply be the one with the strongest teams, or the most strong teams.<ref name=\"surprises\"/><ref name=\"upi19may\"/><ref name=\"norman-chad\"/> Using FIFA World Rankings as a measure of the strength of the teams, ''[[The Guardian]]'' calculated in 2007 that the strongest \"Group of Death\" was [[UEFA Euro 1996 Group C|Euro 1996 Group C]]. The teams (and world rankings) were Germany (2), Russia (3), Italy (7) and the Czech Republic (10).<ref name=\"knowledge\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/dec/12/theknowledge.sport |title=The Knowledge: the deadliest group of death ever |first=John |last=Ashdown |author2=Alan Gardner |author3=James Dart  |work=The Guardian |date=12 December 2007 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Lacey\"/><ref name=\"easygroup\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/dec/11/sport.worldcup20062 |title=An easy group? Draw your own conclusions |first=Paul |last=Wilson |work=The Observer |date=11 December 2005 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref> This record was exceeded by the May 2012 rankings for [[UEFA Euro 2012 Group B|Euro 2012 Group B]], with Germany (2), the Netherlands (4), Portugal (5) and Denmark (10),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/jun/06/success-club-country-without-league-title|title=The Knowledge: Euro 2012 special, part one|last=Steinberg|first=Jacob|date=6 June 2012|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> but not the June rankings immediately before the tournament (3, 4, 10 and 9 respectively)<ref name=\"Associated Press\">{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/story/_/id/8015433/top-10-fifa-rankings-shaken-united-states-moves-28th |title=Spain still No. 1 in FIFA rankings |agency=Associated Press |publisher=ESPN.com |date=6 June 2012 |accessdate=8 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608073245/http://espn.go.com/sports/soccer/story/_/id/8015433/top-10-fifa-rankings-shaken-united-states-moves-28th |archivedate=8 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"uk.eurosport.yahoo.com\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/video/03122011/58/euro-2012-group-b-bosses-react-group-death.html |title=Euro 2012 Group B: Bosses react to 'Group of Death' - Yahoo! Eurosport UK |publisher=Uk.eurosport.yahoo.com |accessdate=23 June 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120408232702/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/video/03122011/58/euro-2012-group-b-bosses-react-group-death.html |archivedate=8 April 2012}}</ref> In [[Women's association football|women's football]], [[2007 FIFA Women's World Cup#Group B|2007 World Cup Group B]] featured three of the top five teams in the [[FIFA Women's World Rankings]] entering the tournament \u2013&nbsp;the [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]] (1), [[Sweden women's national football team|Sweden]] (3) and [[North Korea women's national football team|North Korea]] (5) \u2013 with [[Nigeria women's national football team|Nigeria]] (24) being the \"minnows\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/worldcup/2007-09-11-us-game-1_N.htm |title=USA's group tied in knots after World Cup openers |first=Sal |last=Ruibal |newspaper=USA Today |date=12 September 2007 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |quote=At the 2007 FIFA Women's World Cup, they call Group B the Group of Death because its quartet of high-ranked and unpredictable teams are capable of defeating any opponent. . . . But after Tuesday's pair of gloomy, rain-drenched opening ties [i.e. [[Tie (draw)|draw]]s], Group B has suddenly become sudden death.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/print?id=424508&type=story |title=U.S. women face Group of Death scenario again |first=Graham |last=Hays |publisher=ESPNsoccernet |date=23 April 2007 |accessdate=17 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525153029/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/print?id=424508&type=story |archivedate=25 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nThere may be an emphasis on the \"group of death\" having a tight finish, with all four teams in contention.<ref name=\"Reyna\"/> This was the case in [[1990 FIFA World Cup#Group F|Group F of the 1990 World Cup]], in which five of the six matches were drawn,<ref>{{cite news |title=Speculation not for Robson |first=Stuart |last=Jones |work=The Times |date=14 June 1990 |location=Cagliari |quote=The Group of Death, as the Italians call the World Cup group confined to the islands of Sardinia and Sicily, promises to come to the most dramatic conclusion of the first round. The four teams are inseparable and, whatever the results this weekend, the permutations cannot be fully unravelled until the closing fixtures on June 21. }}</ref> and in [[1994 FIFA World Cup#Group E|Group E of the 1994 World Cup]], when all four teams finished level on points and [[goal difference]].<ref name=\"Haydon\"/>\n\nHowever, the label is usually applied in anticipation of the tournament rather than in retrospect.<ref name=\"Hawkey\"/> Simon Burnton comments, \"Inevitably, one of the big teams involved gets so scared about being in the Group of Death that they play really badly, meaning not only that they go home in disappointment and disgrace, but that the group turns out not to be so very troublesome after all.\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2009/mar/21/burnton-saturday-column |title=Forget Death \u2013 what about a Group of Poop? |first=Simon |last=Burnton |work=The Guardian |date=21 March 2009 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref> David Lacey said, \"Draws may nominate a group of death but results decide its real mortality rating.  France and Argentina found this out in Japan.\"<ref name=\"Lacey\"/> Lacey also said, \"There are groups of death and groups of death wishes. In Euro 2000 [[UEFA Euro 2000#Group D|Group D]] looked daunting but was shrugged aside by the Netherlands, the co-hosts, and France, the eventual champions, with the Czechs, runners-up in 1996, and the Danes, winners in 1992, offering scant resistance. [[UEFA Euro 2000#Group A|Group A]] turned out to be the killer.\"\n\nLack of consensus about which is the group of death can fuel debates among fans and journalists.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/jun/19/match.sport |title=Milosevic breathes life into the group of death |page=A5 |first=Roy |last=Collins |work=The Guardian |date=19 June 2000  |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=People love talking about groups of death at European Championships, World Cups and even the Champions League.}}</ref> In the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]], ''The Guardian'' called [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group F|Group F]] (Sweden, England, Argentina and [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]]) \"the group of death\"<ref name=\"Lacey\"/><ref name=\"life2002\">{{cite news |url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/worldcup2002/countries/page/0,,719107,00.html |title=World Cup 2002: Russia's group |work=The Guardian |date=2 December 2001 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=Compared to England's group of death, this [sc. [[2002 FIFA World Cup - Group H|Group H]]] is a group of life. }}</ref> and [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group E|Group E]] (Germany, the Republic of Ireland, Cameroon and [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]]) \"the other Group of Death\".<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=26 May 2002 |page=8 (Sport) |title=Best bets: stick with France and ignore the buzz |author=\"Mr Prospector\" }}</ref> South Koreans called [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group D|Group D]] ([[South Korea national football team|South Korea]], [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]], Portugal and [[Poland national football team|Poland]]) the \"Real Group of Death\".<ref>\n{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/jun/11/worldcupfootball2002.sport2 |title=Korea get attack of the jitters after Friedel frustrates |first=Jon |last=Brodkin |work=The Guardian |pages=D10\u201311 |date=11 June 2002 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref> In the 2006 World Cup, both [[2006 FIFA World Cup Group C|Group C]] (Argentina, the Netherlands, Ivory Coast and [[Serbia and Montenegro national football team|Serbia and Montenegro]])<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jun/10/worldcup2006.sport18 |title=Kezman's inside knowledge of Holland may see Serbs strike fatal blow in Group of Death |first=Michael |last=Walker |work=The Guardian |date=10 June 2006 |location=Leipzig |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=No World Cup is complete without either a Group of Death or a sticker album, and Group C delivers both items }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2005/dec/10/newsstory.sport6 |title=Argentina join the Dutch in group of death |first=Paul |last=Kelso |work=The Guardian |date=10 December 2005 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}\n</ref> and [[2006 FIFA World Cup Group E|Group E]] (Italy, [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]], Czech Republic and the United States)<ref name=\"easygroup\"/> were nominated as \"group of death\".<ref name=\"Reyna\"/> In the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]], three groups were acknowledged in the media as \"group of death\": [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group B|Group B]] (Spain, the Netherlands, [[Chile national football team|Chile]], [[Australia national soccer team|Australia]]),<ref name=\"Jackson\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/dec/06/world-cup-2014-draw-group-death-spain |title=World Cup 2014 draw: Spain and Holland in 'group of death' |first=Jamie |last=Jackson |work=The Guardian |date=6 December 2013 |accessdate=6 December 2013 }}</ref> [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group D|Group D]] ([[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]], [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]], England and [[Italy national football team|Italy]]),<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/dec/06/world-cup-2014-england-group-death-brazil |title=World Cup 2014: England to kick off 'group of death' in the jungle |first=Owen |last=Gibson |work=The Guardian |date=6 December 2013 |accessdate=6 December 2013 }}</ref> and [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group G|Group G]] (Germany, Portugal, Ghana and the United States);<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/worldcup/2013/12/06/2014-world-cup-usa-draw-group-of-death-ghana-portugal-germany/3892009/ |title=U.S. drawn into World Cup 'Group of Death': Ghana, Portugal, Germany |work=USA Today |date=6 December 2013 |accessdate=6 December 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://prosoccertalk.nbcsports.com/2013/12/06/world-cup-2014-groups-of-death-from-deadly-to-deadliest/ |title=World Cup 2014 Groups of Death: From Deadly to Deadliest |first=Nicholas |last=Mendola |work=NBC Sports |date=6 December 2013 |accessdate=6 December 2013 }}</ref> Group G was considered especially difficult in the U.S., as they had been eliminated by its \"weakest\" team, Ghana, in each of the past two tournaments. In the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]], there were three groups that were considered groups of death: [[2018 FIFA World Cup Group E|Group E]] ([[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]], [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]] and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]]), [[2018 FIFA World Cup Group F|Group F]] ([[2014 FIFA World Cup Final|reigning champions]] [[Germany national football team|Germany]], [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] and [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]]) and [[2018 FIFA World Cup Group D|Group D]] ([[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]], [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] and [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/world-cup-groups-of-death-over-the-years-which-teams-should/1k6od8ho35kas15rgajikwn5no|title=World Cup 'Groups of Death' over the years & which teams should be afraid in Russia 2018 {{!}} Goal.com|access-date=2018-08-20|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2017\u201318 UEFA Champions League group stage]], Group H ([[Real Madrid]], [[Tottenham Hotspur]], [[Borussia Dortmund]] and [[APOEL]]) and in the [[2019\u201320 UEFA Champions League group stage]], Group F ([[SK Slavia Prague]],[[Inter Milan]],[[Borussia Dortmund]],and [[FC Barcelona|FC Barcelona,]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/08/29/football/champions-league-draw-barcelona-liverpool-spt-intl/index.html|title=Barcelona drawn in Champions League 'group of death'|last=CNN|first=Matias Grez|website=CNN|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>) was considered \"the group of death\".\n\nIn the 1998-99 UEFA Champions League group stage there were six group which all of them contained four teams, but only the group winners and the two second-placed teams with the best records would qualify for the next round. In that season, Group C (Holders Real Madrid, 1998 UEFA Cup Winners Internazionale, 1998 UEFA Cup semi-finalists Spartak Moscow and comparative minoows Sturm Graz) and Group D (Spanish champions Barcelona, former Champions Cup winners Bayern Munich and Manchester United as well as relative minnows Br\u00f8ndby) could well be considered group of deaths. In the event, those groups were the two whose second-placed teams would go on to have the best records among second-placed teams, and the top two teams of Group D, Bayern Munich and Manchester United, would actually go on to contest the final (ironically in the stadium of the \"big\" eliminated team of the group, the Camp Nou where FC Barcelona play.\n\nFans may describe as the \"group of death\" any tough group which contains their favoured team. [[George Vecsey]] says, \"In soccer, every nation always thinks it has been stiffed into the toughest pool, the Group of Death.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C04E6DD113CF935A2575BC0A9619C8B63 |title=An American in the World Cup Is Dreaming Big |last=Vecsey |first=George |date=16 August 2007|work=New York Times |accessdate=4 December 2009}}</ref> In this sense, David Warren comments that a \"top seeding in a finals group gives a country a good chance to advance and the best chance to avoid a so-called group of death\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://goal.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/09/10/the-road-to-south-africa/ |title=Road to South Africa |last=Warren |first=David |date=10 September 2009 |series=Goal blog|work=New York Times|accessdate=4 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Other sports==\nThe label \"group of death\" has been used in other sports than association football; for example:\n;[[Basketball]]: [[1994 FIBA World Championship#Group A|1994 FIBA World Championship Group A]];<ref>{{cite news |publisher=Agence France Presse |title=World Championship |date=2 August 1994 |quote=China was 17th at Barcelona and slotted in what coach Jiang Xingquan calls the group of death, against three teams China has never bested. }}</ref> [[2010 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament#Midwest Regional \u2013 St. Louis, Missouri|2010 NCAA Men's Midwest Regional]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/discussion/2010/03/08/DI2010030803202.html  |title=Tiger Woods at the Masters return, NCAA Tournament, NBA and more |last=Wilbon |first=Michael |authorlink=Michael Wilbon |date=16 March 2010 |series=The Chat House with Michael Wilbon |work=Washington Post|quote=Georgetown and Maryland, of course, is in that Group of Death Midwest region where you've got Tennessee, Ohio State, Oklahoma State, Michigan State, a totally known but damn good Iowa State team. Why the NCAA Tournament would stack the region where the overall No. 1 is I don't know |accessdate=27 March 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tri-cityherald.com/2010/03/17/941727/a-fair-bit-of-chalk-ending-in.html |title=My chalky bracket ends in Jayhawk |last=Degerman |first=Eric |date=17 March 2010 |work=Rub of the Green |publisher=Tri-City Herald |quote=the Midwest bracket, dubbed \"The Group of Death\" by those who follow World Cup soccer |accessdate=27 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229162617/http://www.tri-cityherald.com/2010/03/17/941727/a-fair-bit-of-chalk-ending-in.html |archivedate=29 February 2012}}</ref> [[2014 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament#Midwest Regional \u2013 Indianapolis, Indiana|2014 NCAA Men's Midwest Regional]] (where undefeated Wichita State was pitted in an early round against a young, talented Kentucky team playing far better than their ranking would suggest, and in a bracket which also included powerhouses Michigan, Duke and Louisville);<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/collegebasketballnation/post/_/id/96336/bracket-winners-and-losers-2 |title=Bracket winners and losers |work=Men's College Basketball Blog |first=Andy |last=Katz |authorlink=Andy Katz |publisher=[[ESPN.com]] |quote=The [[2013\u201314 Wichita State Shockers men's basketball team|Shockers]] did earn a No. 1 seed with an undefeated season. But they were given the \"Group of Death\" bracket with No. 8 [[2013\u201314 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team|Kentucky]] (if it gets past [[2013\u201314 Kansas State Wildcats men's basketball team|Kansas State]]), No. 4 [[2013\u201314 Louisville Cardinals men's basketball team|Louisville]], No. 3 [[2013\u201314 Duke Blue Devils men's basketball team|Duke]] and No. 2 [[2013\u201314 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|Michigan]]. Wow. |date=16 March 2014 |accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref> [[2016 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament#East Regional \u2013 Philadelphia, PA|2016 NCAA Men's East Regional]];<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/16-things-to-know-about-the-ncaa-east-region--plus-who-wins-170126104.html |title=16 things to know about the NCAA East Region, plus who wins |first=Pat |last=Forde |authorlink=Pat Forde |work=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |quote=Toughest of the four [regions]. Three teams won a major-conference title. Five teams are in the [[Ken Pomeroy|Pomeroy]] Ratings top 15. This is your group of death. |date=14 March 2016 |accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> [[2019 FIBA Basketball World Cup#Group H|2019 FIBA World Cup Group H]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ca.nba.com/news/fiba-basketball-world-cup-2019-canada-draw-group-of-death-with-australia-lithuania-senegal/sq2duek0iypj1k1iu36ubo1dv|title=FIBA Basketball World Cup 2019: Canada draws 'group of death' with Australia, Lithuania, Senegal|last=Gay|first=Carlan|date=16 March 2019|website=NBA.com|access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n;[[Rugby union]]: [[1995 Rugby World Cup#Pool B|1995 World Cup Pool B]];<ref name=\"carling\">{{cite news |title=In Brief |work=Herald Sun |date=22 May 1995 |location=Australia |quote=Carling insists that England's pool is \"the group of death\", rather than the section containing Australia, South Africa, Canada and Romania which already has been given that lurid tag }}</ref> [[2001\u201302 Heineken Cup#Pool 6|2001\u201302 Heineken Cup Pool 6]];<ref>{{cite news |page=A21 |title=Falcons' fatal blow in Group of Death |first=Bryn |last=Palmer |work=The Guardian |date=1 October 2001 }}</ref> [[2003 Rugby World Cup#Group A|2003 World Cup Group A]];<ref>{{cite news |p=32 |title=A man born to take centre stage |first=Brian |last=O'Driscoll |work=The Guardian |date=7 October 2003 |quote=[Ireland] are in the so-called Group of Death with Argentina and the host nation. }}</ref> [[2011\u201312 Heineken Cup#Pool 3|2011-12 Heineken Cup Pool 3]] ([[Glasgow Warriors]] were drawn against reigning champions [[Leinster Rugby|Leinster]], a young [[Bath Rugby|Bath]] side and the best of the lowest-seeded teams [[Montpellier H\u00e9rault Rugby|Montpellier]]); [[2007 Rugby World Cup - Pool D|2007 World Cup Pool D]];<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2007/sep/02/comment.comment1 |title=Let the beauty of rugby shine out in France |first=Alan |last=Ruddock |work=The Observer |date=2 September 2007 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=If Ireland is in the inevitable group of death alongside France and Argentina, then England's is the group of attrition}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2007/sep/06/guardianextra11.guardianspecial921 |title=Is this Ireland's moment? |first1=Michael |last1=Cheika |authorlink1=Michael Cheika |first2=Jason |last2=Leonard |authorlink2=Jason Leonard |work=The Guardian |date=7 September 2007 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref> [[2011 Rugby World Cup Pool B]]; [[2015 Rugby World Cup Pool A]] (where Australia, hosts England and Wales were placed in the same group, being second, third and fourth respectively in the World Rugby rankings as of 21 September 2015<ref>http://www.worldrugby.org/rankings</ref>); [[2019 Rugby World Cup Pool C]]\n;[[Paralympic association football]]: [[Football 7-a-side at the 2012 Summer Paralympics#Group B|2012 Summer Paralympics 7-a-side Group B]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympic-sport/9290076/London-2012-Paralympics-Great-Britain-seven-a-side-footballers-drawn-in-Group-of-Death-at-Games.html|title=London 2012 Paralympics: Great Britain seven-a-side footballers drawn in 'Group of Death' at Games|access-date=2016-09-12}}</ref> [[Football 7-a-side at the 2016 Summer Paralympics#Group A|2016 Summer Paralympics 7-a-side Group A]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/sport/soccer/little-cheer-for-irelands-paralympic-seven-a-side-team-at-home-of-football-420148.html|title=Little cheer for Ireland's Paralympic seven-a-side team at home of football|access-date=2016-09-12}}</ref> [[Football 5-a-side at the 2016 Summer Paralympics#Group B|2016 Summer Paralympics 5-a-side Group B]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/news/football-5-a-side-will-be-tight-but-can-anyone-beat-triple-paralympic-champions-brazil |title=Football 5-a-side will be tight, but can anyone beat triple Paralympic champions Brazil? |website=Rio 2016 |access-date=2016-09-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922202352/https://www.rio2016.com/en/paralympics/news/football-5-a-side-will-be-tight-but-can-anyone-beat-triple-paralympic-champions-brazil |archivedate=22 September 2016}}</ref> \n;[[Rugby league]]: [[1995 Rugby League World Cup#Group 3|1995 World Cup Group 3]];<ref>{{cite news |page=65 |title=Death or Glory! |first=Jonathan |last=Davies |work=Sunday Mirror |date=8 October 1995 |quote=Wales tackle France in our opening fixture in what has chillingly been dubbed the Group of Death. }}</ref> [[2008 Rugby League World Cup#Group A|2008 World Cup Group A]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2008/sep/28/rugbyleagueworldcup2008.rugbyleague |title=The briefing: The Rugby League World Cup, 25 October - 22 November |first=R |last=W |work=The Observer |date=28 September 2008  |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote='A' is the group of death - Australia, New Zealand, England and Papua New Guinea }}</ref> (the 2008 group was deliberately constructed by putting the top four seeds in one group, with three to qualify, to ensure more competitive matches in the first phase, and guarantee weaker sides a semi-final place)\n;[[Cricket]]: [[2008 Twenty20 Cup North Division]];<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/2299392/Lancashires-Steven-Croft-has-perfect-timing.html |title=Lancashire's Steven Croft has perfect timing |last=Collomosse |first=Andrew |date=5 May 2008|work=Daily Telegraph |accessdate=4 December 2009|location=Old Trafford }}</ref> [[2009 ICC World Twenty20#Group C|2009 World Twenty20 Group C]];,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/twenty20/5430945/World-Twenty20-Super-Eights-guide-West-Indies.html |title=World Twenty20 Super Eights guide: West Indies |last=Collins |first=Nick Published |date=10 June 2009|work=Daily Telegraph |accessdate=4 December 2009 |quote=Having survived the \"group of death\" in the opening round, the West Indies find themselves in a similar position at the super eight stage}}</ref> [[2012 ICC World Twenty20#Super8 - Group 2|2012 World Twenty20 Super8 - Group 2]]\n;[[Ice hockey]]: [[Ice hockey at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's qualification#Group G|2010 Olympic men's qualifying group G]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://slapshot.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/02/07/european-puck-germany-to-the-2010-olympics/ |title=European Puck: Germany to the 2010 Olympics |last=Klein |first=Jeff Z. |date=7 February 2009|series=Slap shot blog|work=New York Times|accessdate=4 December 2009 |quote=Meanwhile in Group G at Oslo \u2013 the hotly contested \"Group of Death\"}}</ref>\n\n==Variants==\n\n===Variant definitions===\n\"Group of death\" has occasionally been used to characterise a qualifying group in some other way. The southern section preliminary round Group 5 of the 1990-91 [[Football League Trophy|Leyland DAF Cup]] had lowly teams replaying poorly-attended matches;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://homepage.ntlworld.com/jeremy.hicks/flt/flt9091.html |title=Leyland DAF Cup - 1990/91 |first=Jeremy |last=Hicks |work=The Football League Trophy |accessdate=3 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226234154/http://homepage.ntlworld.com/jeremy.hicks/flt/flt9091.html |archivedate=26 February 2009}}</ref> after many postponements, Robert Pryce commented: \"The Leyland Daf Cup Southern Section preliminary round's Group of Death has achieved almost total rigor mortis.\"<ref>{{cite news |page=20 |title=Soccer Diary |first=Robert |last=Pryce |work=The Guardian |date=12 January 1991 |location=London }}</ref>\n\nScotland manager [[Andy Roxburgh]] described [[UEFA Euro 1992 qualifying Group 2|Euro 1992 qualifying Group 2]] as a \"group of death\" in a different sense because of the lack of a glamorous opponent \"to get people out of the house and into [[Hampden Park]].\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Roxburgh sure of delivery - Group Two: Scotland v San Marino |first=Patrick |last=Glenn |work=The Guardian |date=13 November 1991 |location=London |quote=I called this the group of death because there wasn't a big country to brighten it, to capture the imagination, to get people out of the house and into Hampden Park. Romania and Bulgaria have outstanding talents but they are not a draw. The Swiss are the same, emergent and improving, but not attractive. A France, an Italy, a Germany, even an England in our case, was needed to lift the thing. But we have one last chore and the Scotland team I wanted is here.}}</ref> The group combined [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]], [[Romania national football team|Romania]], [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]], [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]], and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]].\n\nThe [[1994 FIFA World Cup qualification (AFC)#Final round|Asian final qualifying group for the 1994 World Cup]] featured two sets of militantly hostile neighbours: Iran, Iraq, and Saudi Arabia; and North Korea, South Korea, and Japan. This was called the \"group of death\" for [[black humour]].<ref>\n{{cite journal |title=Saudi soccer success in Qatar |first=Phil |last=Minshull |work=The Middle East |page=40 |issue=N229 |issn=0305-0734 |date=1 December 1993 |location=Saudi Arabia |quote=Western commentators dubbed the 13-day tournament in Qatar the \"Group of Death\" since fate had brought together six potentially volatile elements.}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news |page=78 |title=The mother of all wars and the father of all football matches? Let's wait and see |first=Alan |last=Fraser |work=Daily Mail |date=22 October 1993 |location=London |quote=The Iraq and Iran footballers have been breakfasting together, chatting even, part of a bizarre logistical cocktail in which the so-called 'group of death' - also including Saudi Arabia, North and South Korea and Japan - have been billeted in the same hotel. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Social Studies |first=Michael |last=Kesterton |work=The Globe and Mail |date=21 October 1993 |location=Canada |quote=The six have been nicknamed the Group of Death, writes Mark Skipworth in The Sunday Times of London. Three of the six - Iran, Iraq and Saudi Arabia - have recently been at war and two others - North and South Korea - have never officially ended their state of conflict. (The sixth team is from Japan.) }}</ref>\n\nA similar quip was made of the [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)#Group 1|UEFA qualifying group 1 for the 1998 World Cup]]:\n{{cquote|The toughest group in the World Cup qualifying competition is the Group of Death. For the 1998 qualifiers, group one takes the title with ease. Bosnia, Croatia and Slovenia were drawn in group one. . . .  There was, mercifully, no Serb-dominated rump Yugoslavia drawn in the same group. But there was, as far as the others are concerned, the next worse thing: the Greeks. They share the Orthodox religion with the Serbs, and give them strong diplomatic support. Pity Denmark, the reigning European champions, who make up the group.<ref>{{cite news |page=1 |title=It's War: World Cup squares up for the battle of the Balkans |first=John |last=Mullin |work=The Guardian |date=13 December 1995 }}</ref>}}\n\n===Related terms===\nOccasionally, alternatives to \"group of death\" are proffered. [[Javier Clemente]] said of [[1998 FIFA World Cup - Group D|1998 World Cup Group D]], \"This is not the group of death, as some people have said. It is the group of heart attacks\"<ref>{{cite news |page=A5 |title=Clemente's hopes may go up in puff of smoke |work=The Guardian |date=24 June 1998 }}</ref> John Harrell said of [[1994 FIFA World Cup#Group E|1994 World Cup Group E]], \"The characterization might be a bit harsh. Perhaps the 'Group of Surprises' is a better term.\"<ref name=\"surprises\"/>\n\nSometimes the excitement of a close contest between high-quality teams has suggested the positive \"group of life\" is more appropriate than \"group of death\".<ref>\n{{cite news|url=http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2006/06/23/story6677.asp |title=Sudden death in group of life |work=Irish Examiner |date=23 June 2006 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=what had turned out to be the World Cup\u2019s Group of Life. The supporters of all four competing nations would have woken up in various cities in Germany yesterday morning with dreams of further glory in their minds. }}{{dead link|date=March 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Of [[2002 FIFA World Cup - Group F|2002 World Cup Group F]], Paul Wilson said, \"England's group is not so much the group of death as the group of life, for few others promise any drama\"<ref name=\"life2002f\"/> Of [[2006 FIFA World Cup Group C|2006 World Cup Group C]], [[Gary Lineker]] said after Argentina's demolition of Serbia and Montenegro, \"Argentina produced one of the great performances in recent World Cup history. The group of death has become the group of life.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/5057832.stm |title=Argentina 6-0 Serbia & Montenegro |work=BBC Sport |date=16 June 2006 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref>\n\nHowever, \"Group of Life\" has also been used as the opposite of \"Group of Death\", to mean an easy group with weak teams: examples include [[2002 FIFA World Cup#Group H|2002 World Cup Group H]];<ref name=\"life2002f\"/><ref>\n{{cite news |url=http://sport.scotsman.com/japansworldcup/Group-H-in-detail.2327985.jp |title=\nGroup H in detail |work=Scotland on Sunday  |date=19 May 2002 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=Tipped to make it through to the knockout stages in only their second World Cup thanks to a very favourable draw into the 'Group of Life' }}</ref> [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification - UEFA Group 6|2006 World Cup UEFA qualifying Group 6]];<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/james-lawton-rooneys-lurking-brilliance-fails-to-instil-hope-of-better-times-for-england-at-the-big-show-510692.html |title=Rooney's lurking brilliance fails to instil hope of better times for England at the Big Show |first=James |last=Lawton |work=The Independent |date=13 October 2005 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=a qualifying pool so benignly unthreatening it might have been known as the Group of Life }}</ref> [[2006 FIFA World Cup Group D|2006 World Cup Group D]];<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/worldcup2006/WORLD-CUP-PREVIEW-We-could.1556397.jp |title=We could be in for a Ruud awakening |first=Alan |last=Swann |work=Peterborough Today |date= June 2006 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=If Group C is the 'Group of Death' then this is the 'Group of Life' }}</ref> [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group C|2010 World Cup Group C]];<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/dec/04/england-world-cup-2010 |title=Lucky England secure place in 'group of life' in football 2010 World Cup draw |first=Paul |last=Hayward |work=[[The Guardian]] |date= 4 December 2009 |location=United Kingdom |accessdate=5 December 2009 |quote=Lucky England secure place in 'group of life' in football 2010 World Cup draw}}</ref> and [[2018 FIFA World Cup#Group A|2018 World Cup Group A]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://amp.businessinsider.com/russia-world-cup-draw-the-group-of-life-2017-12 |title=Charts show that Russia's World Cup group is unlike the others|first=Samantha |last=Lee |work=[[Business Insider]] |date= 2 December 2017 |location=United Kingdom |accessdate=10 June 2018 |quote=there is what some are calling the Group of Life and, coincidentally, it features the host nation, Russia. As for Russia's Group A, those four teams add up to a combined ranking of 180, 77 more than any other group.}}</ref> Chuck Culpepper wrote of [[2006 FIFA World Cup Group B|2006 World Cup Group B]], 'If each World Cup draw brings a \"Group of Death,\" anointed for its incomparable rigor among the eight groups, England 2006 surely occupies the Group of Life, or the Group of Tranquillity, or the Group of So Few Worries We Spent All Day Yesterday Following the [[Wayne Rooney#International career|Metatarsal Melodrama]] Rather Than Worry About [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]].'<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/jun/15/sports/sp-england15 |title=Getting the Group Rate on Life and Death |first=Chuck |last=Culpepper |work=LA Times |date=15 June 2006 |accessdate=3 December 2009 }}</ref> [[Radio T\u00e9l\u00e9vision Suisse]] said Switzerland was \"far from being in a group of 'death'\" when drawn in [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group E|2014 World Cup Group E]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rts.ch/sport/football/international/equipe-suisse/5434964-groupe-mi-figue-mi-raisin-pour-la-suisse-qui-retrouve-la-france.html |title=Groupe mi-figue mi-raisin pour la Suisse, qui retrouve la France |language=fr |publisher=Radio T\u00e9l\u00e9vision Suisse |date=6 December 2014 |accessdate=23 June 2014 |quote=La Suisse se retrouve, en effet, dans le groupe E qui est tr\u00e8s loin de s'apparenter \u00e0 un groupe de la \"mort\".}}</ref> Polish-speaking media tend to refer to relatively tough and forgiving groups as ''grupa \u015bmierci'' (\"group of death\") and ''grupa marze\u0144'' (\"dream group\") respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.przegladsportowy.pl/pilka-nozna/euro-2016,losowanie-grup-euro-2016-grupa-marzen-i-grupa-smierci,artykul,622356,1,12341.html |title=Jaka by\u0142aby grupa marze\u0144 i \u015bmierci Polak\u00f3w na Euro 2016 |publisher=Przegl\u0105d Sportowy |date=18 November 2015 |accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref>{{original research inline|date=July 2016}}\n\n{{anchor|Sleep}}<!-- [[Group of sleep]] redirects here -->[[1986 FIFA World Cup#Group F|1986 World Cup Group F]], with two goals in the first four games combined, was dubbed the \"Group of Sleep\".<ref>\n{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/international/england/3017725/England-pay-for-past-failures.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130421124609/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/international/england/3017725/England-pay-for-past-failures.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=21 April 2013 |title=England pay for past failures |work=Daily Telegraph |date=28 November 2001 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=the Mexicans also gave a title to 1986's Group Six. England, Poland, Portugal and Morocco, the locals in Monterrey were fond of saying, was the 'Group of Sleep'. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/internationals/lisbon-evokes-mixture-of-memories-733305.html |title=Lisbon evokes mixture of memories |first=Tim |last=Rich |work=The Independent |date=24 June 2004 |accessdate=3 December 2009 |quote=the dreadfully dull \"Group of Sleep\" }}</ref>\n\nBefore the [[UEFA Euro 2012]] tournament draw, financial writer Chris Sloley coined the term \"Group of Debt\" for a possible group comprising [[PIGS (economics)|PIIGS]] [[European debt crisis|indebted countries]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://citywire.co.uk/global/football-pundits-eye-potential-group-of-debt-at-euro-2012/a548683 |title=Football pundits eye potential \u2018Group of Debt\u2019 at Euro 2012 |first=Chris |last=Sloley |publisher=[[Citywire]] |date=2 December 2011 |accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref> in the event, three of these ([[Spain national football team|Spain]], [[Italy national football team|Italy]] and the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]]) were grouped together with [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] in [[UEFA Euro 2012 Group C|Group C]], while [[Greece national football team|Greece]] and [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] were in other groups.\n\n\"Group of Champions\" has been used in the [[UEFA Champions League]] both for groups where all teams are former champions of that competition,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/30/sports/soccer/german-and-british-teams-grouped-together-in-champions-league.html|title=German and British Teams Grouped Together in Champions League|last=Das|first=Andrew|date=29 August 2013|work=The New York Times|quote=Barcelona is in what amounts to a Group of Champions with A.C. Milan, Ajax Amsterdam and Glasgow Celtic; those four clubs have combined for 16 European championships.|accessdate=12 July 2016}}; {{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/draw-centre/cup=1/season=2014/round=2000479/|title=UEFA Champions League-Group stage draw-Monaco|date=29 August 2013|publisher=[[UEFA]]|quote=Johan Cruyff on AFC Ajax, who will play AC Milan, FC Barcelona and Celtic FC in Group H: \"It\u2019s a fantastic thing for football that these clubs get drawn against other. It\u2019s another group of champions ...\"|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> and for groups where all teams are reigning domestic champions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/08/30/sport/football/football-champions-league-draw/|title=Group of champions pairs Manchester City and Real Madrid|date=30 August 2012|publisher=[[CNN]]|quote=The \"Group of Death\" contains all champions of their respective leagues with Dortmund claiming the Bundesliga title for the second straight year and Ajax winning the Dutch crown.|accessdate=12 July 2016}}; {{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2914/champions-league/2013/08/29/4223389/champions-league-draw-32-expert-verdicts|title=Champions League draw: The experts' verdict|date=29 August 2013|work=Goal.com|quote=It's not quite the Group of champions that was so disastrous last season|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.whoateallthepies.tv/miscellaneous/4271/the_top_10_foot.html |title=The top seven World Cup Groups of Death |work=Who ate all the Pies |orig-year=3 December 2007 |date=4 December 2009 |author=Ollie }}\n* {{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/columns/story?id=708444&cc=5739&ver=global |title=Five of the best Groups of Death |last=Adams |first=Tom |date=4 December 2009 |work=soccernet |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=4 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091207193353/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/columns/story?id=708444&cc=5739&ver=global |archivedate=7 December 2009}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/rssbest/groupsofdea