s in England]]\n[[Category:Irish radio presenters]]\n[[Category:People educated at Synge Street CBS]]\n[[Category:Irish television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Television personalities from Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:People from Portobello, Dublin]]\n", "name_user": "Maarten1963", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBroadcasting career:corrected link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eamonn_Andrews"}
{"title_page": "Interstate 90 in Idaho", "text_new": "{{highway detail hatnote|Interstate 90}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=ID\n|type=I\n|route=90\n|alternate_name=Purple Heart Trail\n|map={{MapframeForObjects|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Interstate 90 in Idaho}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=I-90 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=73.888\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"milepoint log\">{{cite web|title=Milepoint Log Report|url=http://itd.idaho.gov/highways/milepointlog/logs/interState/I_90_MPLog.pdf|publisher=[[Idaho Transportation Department]]|accessdate=July 11, 2015|format=PDF|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713030426/http://itd.idaho.gov/highways/milepointlog/logs/interState/I_90_MPLog.pdf|archivedate=July 13, 2015}}</ref>\n|established=1957\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=WA|I|90}} at the [[Washington (state)|Washington]] state line\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=ID|SH|41}} in [[Post Falls, Idaho|Post Falls]]\n*{{Jct|state=ID|US|95}} in [[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho|Coeur d'Alene]]\n*{{jct|state=ID|SH|97}} near [[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho|Coeur d'Alene]]\n*{{jct|state=ID|SH|3}} near [[Cataldo, Idaho|Cataldo]]\n*{{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Wallace|SH|4}} in [[Wallace, Idaho|Wallace]]\n}}\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=MT|I|90}} at the [[Montana]] state line\n|counties=[[Kootenai County, Idaho|Kootenai]], [[Shoshone County, Idaho|Shoshone]]\n|previous_type=US\n|previous_route=89\n|next_type=US\n|next_route=91\n}}\n\n'''Interstate&nbsp;90''' ('''I-90''') is a transcontinental [[Interstate Highway System|Interstate Highway]] that runs east\u2013west across the northern United States. Within the state of [[Idaho]], the freeway travels for {{convert|74|mi|km|0}} from the [[Washington (state)|Washington]] border near [[Spokane, Washington|Spokane]] to [[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho|Coeur d'Alene]] and the [[Idaho Panhandle|panhandle region]] at the north end of the state. After traveling through the [[Silver Valley (Idaho)|Silver Valley]] along the [[Coeur d'Alene River]] in the [[Bitterroot Range]], I-90 crosses into [[Montana]] at [[Lookout Pass]].\n\nI-90 was created by the federal government in 1957, following the general route of [[U.S. Route 10 in Idaho|U.S. Route 10]] (US&nbsp;10) and the mid-19th century [[Mullan Road]] constructed by the U.S. Army. The freeway was constructed in stages between 1960 and 1992.\n\n==Route description==\n\nInterstate&nbsp;90 enters Idaho at a crossing of the [[Spokane River]] in the community of [[State Line, Idaho|State Line]] in [[Kootenai County, Idaho|Kootenai County]], approximately {{convert|20|mi|km}} east of [[Spokane, Washington]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Geranios |first=Nicholas K. |date=January 8, 2011 |title=Idaho town to lottery winner: Please show yourself |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-idaho-town-to-lottery-winner-please-show-yourself-2011jan08-story.html |work=[[San Diego Union-Tribune]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=September 24, 2018}}</ref> The freeway travels northeast through the [[Rathdrum Prairie]] and into the outskirts of [[Post Falls, Idaho|Post Falls]], passing several retailers and a [[business park]] along the Spokane River. I-90 continues east along the river, paralleled to the south by the [[North Idaho Centennial Trail]] and a section of the [[BNSF Railway]], and passes near the eponymous [[Post Falls]] and the city's downtown, served by a signed [[business route]]. The freeway intersects [[Idaho State Highway 41|State Highway 41]] (SH-41) and continues through the city's eastern residential neighborhoods and passes the nearby town of [[Huetter, Idaho|Huetter]]. I-90 then reaches [[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho|Coeur d'Alene]], the largest city in northern Idaho, and intersects a business route and [[U.S. Route 95 in Idaho|US-95]], the state's main north\u2013south highway, near the [[Kootenai Medical Center]].<ref name=\"google\">{{google maps |title=Interstate 90 |url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/47.696623,-117.0416018/47.4560707,-115.6953649/@47.5851041,-116.6479888,10z/data=!4m2!4m1!3e0 |accessdate=September 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe freeway travels around the north and east sides of central Coeur d'Alene, intersecting several local streets in the process, and turns southeast towards [[Fernan Lake]] and [[Lake Coeur d'Alene]] on the Spokane River. I-90 ascends Potlatch Hill and makes several stair-step turns to follow the northern shore of Lake Coeur d'Alene while traversing several forested hills. It passes {{convert|240|ft|m}} over a valley overlooking Bennett Bay on the [[Veterans Memorial Centennial Bridge]], a high concrete bridge that was completed in 1987.<ref>{{cite news |date=February 10, 2017 |title=Bennett Bay Bridge offers best of form and function |url=http://apps.itd.idaho.gov/Apps/MediaManagerMVC/transporter/2017/021017_Trans/021017_VaultBennettBayBr.html |work=The Transporter |publisher=Idaho Transportation Department |accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref> The freeway descends from the hills and travels southeasterly along Wolf Lodge Bay, passing [[Coeur d'Alene Parkway State Park]] and intersecting the northern terminus of the [[Lake Coeur d'Alene Scenic Byway]] ([[Idaho State Highway 97|SH-97]]) at the east end of the lake. I-90 continues east along Cedar Creek into the [[Coeur d'Alene Mountains]], part of a [[Coeur d'Alene National Forest|national forest]],<ref name=\"google\"/> and reaches [[Fourth of July Summit]] at an elevation of {{convert|3,173|ft}}.<ref name=\"Spokesman-Passes\">{{cite news |last=Prager |first=Mike |date=May 16, 2017 |title=Snow returns to the mountains, but warmer weather will arrive by the weekend |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2017/may/16/snow-returns-to-the-mountains-but-warmer-weather-w/ |work=The Spokesman-Review |accessdate=September 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:I-90IDWallace.jpg|thumb|Eastbound I-90 on the 1991 viaduct<br/>at [[Wallace, Idaho|Wallace]] in 2007]]\n\nFrom the summit, I-90 continues southeast along Fourth of July Canyon towards the [[Coeur d'Alene River]] valley and intersects [[Idaho State Highway 3|SH-3]] near [[Rose Lake, Idaho|Rose Lake]]. The freeway bends northward around a hill and travels east into the river valley, passing [[Cataldo, Idaho|Cataldo]] and the [[Old Mission State Park]], home to the state's oldest standing building.<ref>{{cite news |date=January 15, 2009 |title=Idaho to cut Cataldo Mission park funding |url=https://missoulian.com/lifestyles/recreation/idaho-to-cut-cataldo-mission-park-funding/article_46fb1220-378a-5f84-97ba-712bdf27938f.html |work=[[Missoulian]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref> In Cataldo, it also crosses the river and the [[Trail of the Coeur d'Alenes]], a major rail trail that follows the highway into the [[Bitterroot Range]].<ref name=\"Kitsap-Trail\">{{cite news |last=Blair Jr. |first=Seabury |date=September 25, 2007 |title=72 Miles of Idaho Fun |page=17 |work=[[Kitsap Sun]] |url=http://archive.kitsapsun.com/outdoors/72-miles-of-idaho-fun-ep-422743545-358852731.html |accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref> I-90 crosses into [[Shoshone County, Idaho|Shoshone County]], one of only two counties along the highway within Idaho,<ref>{{cite news |last=Dukes |first=Lucy |date=March 15, 2008 |title=Pick Of The Litter? |page=C1 |work=[[The Coeur d'Alene Press]]}}</ref> and continues along the north sides of [[Pinehurst, Idaho|Pinehurst]] and [[Smelterville, Idaho|Smelterville]], passing the [[Shoshone County Airport]] at the latter. The freeway travels southeasterly through [[Kellogg, Idaho|Kellogg]], passing the [[Silver Mountain Resort]] and its [[ski gondola]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Geranios |first=Nicholas K. |date=September 16, 2007 |title=Silver lining \u2014 Former Idaho mining town finds new life as swanky ski resort |work=Missoulian |agency=Associated Press |url=https://missoulian.com/business/silver-lining-former-idaho-mining-town-finds-new-life-as/article_accea8e1-564f-5aba-872e-febf04a65d09.html |accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref> and continues around the towns of [[Osburn, Idaho|Osburn]] and [[Silverton, Idaho|Silverton]] along the north bank of the [[South Fork Coeur d'Alene River]] at the bottom of the narrow [[Silver Valley (Idaho)|Silver Valley]].<ref name=\"google\"/> I-90 also intersects a set of business routes in Osburn and Silverton that loop back to the freeway.\n\nThe freeway turns east in the town of [[Wallace, Idaho|Wallace]], also served by its own business route, and travels to the north of downtown on an elevated viaduct cut into a nearby hill.<ref>{{cite news |last=Prager |first=Mike |date=May 3, 2010 |title=Wallace honoring savior |page=A8 |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2010/may/03/wallace-honoring-savior/ |work=The Spokesman-Review |accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref> At the east end of Wallace, I-90 intersects [[Idaho State Highway 4|SH-4]], which connects to the [[ghost town]] of [[Burke, Idaho|Burke]]. The highway continues along the south side of the river and Trail of the Coeur d'Alenes as it ascends further into the mountains and meanders around hills and gulches.<ref>{{cite news |last=Malgesini |first=Tammy |date=August 18, 2012 |title=Rich history of Wallace |work=[[East Oregonian]]}}</ref> The trail ends at the town of [[Mullan, Idaho|Mullan]],<ref name=\"Kitsap-Trail\"/> named for road-building U.S. Army captain [[John Mullan (road builder)|John Mullan]] and home to a business route,<ref name=\"AP-Mullan\">{{cite news |last=Geranios |first=Nicholas K. |date=June 15, 2003 |title=Little-Known Road Played Big Role in Conquest of the West |page=A28 |work=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |agency=Associated Press |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/jun/15/news/adna-mullan15 |accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref> and I-90 continues east along the [[Northern Pacific Trail]]. The freeway travels uphill from the river along a southern ridge and passes a [[scenic viewpoint]] commemorating the 1903 [[Willow Creek avalanche]].<ref>https://history.idaho.gov/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Idaho-Highway-Historical-Marker-Guide.pdf</ref>{{cn|date=September 2018}} I-90 then turns south and leaves Idaho at [[Lookout Pass]], elevated {{convert|4,725|ft}} above sea level and located adjacent to the [[Lookout Pass Ski and Recreation Area]].<ref name=\"google\"/><ref name=\"Spokesman-Passes\"/> The freeway [[Interstate 90 in Montana|continues]] into [[Montana]] and travels through the cities of [[Butte, Montana|Butte]], [[Bozeman, Montana|Bozeman]], and [[Billings, Montana|Billings]].<ref>{{cite map |year=2016 |title=Montana Highway Map |publisher=[[Montana Department of Transportation]] |location=Helena, Montana |scale=Scale not given |url=https://mdt.mt.gov/travinfo/docs/2016-mt-highway-map.pdf |accessdate=September 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nI-90 is the only Interstate in [[Idaho Panhandle|northern Idaho]] and a major east\u2013west route,<ref name=\"map\">{{citation |title=Idaho Official Highway Map |publisher=[[Idaho Department of Transportation]] |year=2007 |edition=2007 |place=[[Boise, Idaho|Boise]], [[Idaho]]}}</ref> forming part of a transcontinental highway. At {{convert|74|mi|km}}, it is the second-shortest mainline Interstate in the state, after [[Interstate 86 (Idaho)|Interstate 86]], and the third-longest.{{cn|date=October 2018}} The entire highway was designated as the [[Purple Heart]] Trail by the state legislature in 2008.<ref>{{cite news |last=Russell |first=Betsy |date=August 12, 2014 |title=I-84 now officially Vietnam Veterans Memorial Highway |url=http://www.spokesman.com/blogs/boise/2014/aug/12/i-84-now-officially-vietnam-veterans-memorial-highway/ |work=[[The Spokesman-Review]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Idaho Statues 40-513C: Designation of Purple Heart Trail |year=2008 |url=https://legislature.idaho.gov/statutesrules/idstat/title40/t40ch5/sect40-513c/ |publisher=[[Idaho Legislature]] |accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> The Idaho section of I-90 is maintained by the [[Idaho Transportation Department]] (ITD), which conducts an annual survey of traffic on certain highway segments that is expressed in terms of [[average annual daily traffic]] (AADT), a measure of traffic volume for any average day of the year. Traffic volumes on I-90 ranged from a minimum of 7,861 near Mullan and 60,729 in Huetter on an average day in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=ATR & WIM Data: Interstate 90 |url=https://apps.itd.idaho.gov/apps/roadwaydata/Maps/ATR_I90_list.html |publisher=Idaho Transportation Department |accessdate=September 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nInterstate 90 from Coeur d'Alene to Lookout Pass roughly follows the route of the [[Mullan Road]], constructed in 1859\u201360 by the U.S. Army and civilian volunteers led by captain [[John Mullan (road builder)|John Mullan]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Mccroskeyjeri Mccroskey |first=Jerry |date=June 4, 2005 |title=John Mullan created road with future travelers in mind |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2005/jun/04/john-mullan-created-road-with-future-travelers-in/ |work=The Spokesman-Review |accessdate=September 24, 2018}}</ref> Mullan received a series of appropriations from U.S. Congress from 1855 to 1860, totaling $230,000, to build the first engineered road west of the [[Mississippi River]] and connect [[Fort Walla Walla]] to [[Fort Benton, Montana|Fort Benton]].<ref name=\"AP-Mullan\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Kramer |first=Becky |date=July 4, 2005 |title=A road to remember |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2005/jul/04/a-road-to-remember/ |work=The Spokesman-Review |accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> The road also followed the [[Coeur d'Alene River]] and its south fork, which was long used by the [[Coeur d'Alene people]] to visit hunting grounds in modern-day [[Montana]].<ref name=\"Schwieterman\">{{cite book |last=Schwieterman |first=Joseph P. |year=2004 |title=When the Railroad Leaves Town: American Communities in the Age of Rail Line Abandonment |pages=124\u2013128 |publisher=[[Truman State University Press]] |location=Kirksville, Missouri |isbn=1-931112-13-4 |oclc=56968524 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kzk_m4P9Y6kC |via=Google Books |accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOther sections of I-90 were built over the [[Yellowstone Trail]] and [[U.S. Route 10 in Idaho|U.S. Route 10]],<ref name=ietlfwy>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Lc8zAAAAIBAJ&sjid=avcDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7087%2C4638462 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |agency=Associated Press |title=Idaho eyes twin-level freeway |date=December 18, 1963 |page=6 }}</ref> though some parts of I-90 were cut as new roadway.<ref name=nwrow57>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VPxXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6PYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5498%2C155350 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |title=Idaho seeking funds to buy right of way for freeway route |date=February 1, 1957|page=a3}}</ref><ref name=displres>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kZ5YAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hvgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7073%2C4319199 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |agency=Associated Press |last=Leeright |first=Bob |title=Displaced residents add to cost of highways |date=July 31, 1971|page=5}}</ref> The link from Post Falls to the Washington state border was completed in 1972 at a cost of $1.1 million to upgrade the existing road and build a new bridge over the Spokane River.<ref name=frwncom>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CaJYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mfgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7161%2C2273838 |work=Spokane Daily Chronicle |last=Evarts |first=J. Neal|title=Freeway work nears completion |date=October 9, 1972 |page=1 |via=Google News Archive |accessdate=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe small town of [[Wallace, Idaho|Wallace]] in the Silver Valley still prides itself on having what was the last stoplight on I-90. Its downtown has many historical buildings, which would have been wiped out by the original planned route of the freeway,<ref name=wallccexp>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vLwzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=L_gDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4669%2C2078459 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |title=Plans for Interstate 90 explained to Wallace CC |date=January 23, 1970 |page=3 }}</ref><ref name=wcsi90shf>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=16hYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tvgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4551%2C1134583 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |title=Wallace Chamber seeks I-90 shift |date=January 18, 1973 |page=b3 }}</ref> so in 1976, city leaders had the downtown placed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=wfwhrgo>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=W_dLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ne0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6862%2C2634191 |newspaper=Spokesman-Review |location=Spokane, Washington |agency=Associated Press |title=Wallace freeway hearing ordered by federal judge|date=July 23, 1976|page=13}}</ref><ref name=sinchst>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=d0FYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KvkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4800%2C2425121 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |title=I-90 study includes historic site survey |date=January 10, 1980 |page=10 }}</ref><ref name=wfw12yrovd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=D1VOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xu4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6844%2C4794390 |newspaper=Spokesman-Review |location=Spokane, Washington |last=Collin|first=Matthew |title=Wallace freeway 12 years overdue |date=January 26, 1981 |page=6 }}</ref> Alternatives discussed in 1963 included tunnels and twin levels.<ref name=ietlfwy/><ref name=fwyaltrv>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=r1ZOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FfkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4581%2C2716011 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |agency=Associated Press |title=Freeway alternatives reviewed for Wallace |date=October 25, 1978 |page=5 }}</ref>\n\nAs a result, the federal government was forced at great expense to reroute the freeway to the northern edge of downtown and elevate it. Work on that section was resumed in 1984,<ref name=wbwtst>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YFhWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=--4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3163%2C1053173|newspaper=Spokesman-Review |location=Spokane, Washington |last=Bond |first=Dave |title=Wallace bypass work to start |date=July 18, 1984 |page=1}}</ref> and it opened in September 1991.<ref name=\"itd\">[http://itd.idaho.gov/50.Years/I-50_I-90.html Idaho Transportation Department] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060926064753/http://itd.idaho.gov/50.Years/I-50_I-90.html |date=September 26, 2006 }}</ref> A bicycle path is routed beneath part of that segment. Before the move to the viaduct, I-90 went from a freeway at the western edge of Wallace, then turned to surface streets and followed the main arterial as U.S. Route 10 through town, which included the last stoplight on I-90 between Seattle and Boston.<ref name=hsi90riotn>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=JRBWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=S-IDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5671%2C3457563 |newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=Oregon |agency=Associated Press |title=He stalled Interstate 90 right in the middle of town |date=February 13, 1981|page=15F}}</ref> Upon reaching the eastern edge of the town it became a limited access divided highway once again.<ref name=lstplt>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=tJtTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=c4YDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7050%2C6073186 |newspaper=The Bulletin |location=Bend, Oregon |agency=Associated Press |title=Lone stoplight on Interstate 90 to pass by after new bypass |date=September 8, 1991 |page=A9 }}</ref>\n\nThe interstate also was routed along [[Lake Coeur d'Alene]] as a surface street before the [[Veterans Memorial Centennial Bridge]] was completed in 1992, traveling further above the lake.<ref name=\"Spokesman-50\">{{cite news |last=Cannata |first=Amy |date=September 10, 2006 |title=Freeway at 50 |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2006/sep/10/freeway-at-50/ |work=Spokesman-Review |accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Exit list==\n{{Jcttop|exit|length_ref=<ref name=\"milepoint log\"/>|exit_ref=<ref name=\"milepoint log\"/>}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|county=Kootenai\n|cspan=18\n|location=none\n|mile=0.000\n|road={{Jct|state=WA|I|90|dir1=West|city1=Spokane}}\n|notes=Continuation into Washington\n}}\n{{anchor|Spokane River Bridge}}\n{{Jctbridge|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=0.000\n|mile2=0.098\n|bridge=Bridge over [[Spokane River]]\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=Post Falls\n|lspan=5\n|mile=1.160\n|exit=1\n|road=Beck Road (via Pointe Parkway)\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|mile=2.080\n|exit=2\n|road=Pleasant View Road\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|mile=4.632\n|exit=5\n|road={{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Post Falls|dir1=east|name1=Spokane Street|location1=[[City Center (Post Falls, Idaho)|City Center]]}}\n|notes=Exit is just east of northernmost point on I-90\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=5.450\n|exit=6\n|road={{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Post Falls|dir1=west|name1=Seltice Way / 4th Avenue|location1=[[City Center (Post Falls, Idaho)|City Center]]}}\n|notes=Westbound exit and eastbound entrance\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|mile=7.128\n|exit=7\n|road={{jct|state=ID|SH|41|dir1=north|city1=Rathdrum|city2=Spirit Lake}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=Coeur d'Alene\n|lspan=5\n|mile=11.290\n|exit=11\n|road={{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Coeur d'Alene|dir1=east|name1=Northwest Boulevard|location1=[[City Center (Coeur d'Alene, Idaho)|City Center]]}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|mile=12.040\n|exit=12\n|road={{jct|state=ID|US|95|city1=Sandpoint|city2=Moscow|name1=Lincoln Way|location3=[[Silverwood Theme Park|Silverwood]]|location4=[[British Columbia Highway 95|Canada]]}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|mile=12.560\n|exit=13\n|road=4th Street\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|mile=13.560\n|exit=14\n|road=15th Street\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|mile=14.780\n|exit=15\n|road={{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Coeur d'Alene|dir1=west|name1=Sherman Avenue|city1=Fernan|location1=[[City Center (Coeur d'Alene, Idaho)|City Center]]}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=16.882\n|exit=17\n|road=Mullan Trail Road\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=22.063\n|exit=22\n|road={{jct|state=ID|SH|97|dir1=south|city1=Harrison|city2=St. Maries}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=28.380\n|exit=28\n|road=Fourth of July Pass Recreation Area\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=34.028\n|exit=34\n|road={{jct|state=ID|SH|3|dir1=south|city1=Rose Lake|city2=St. Maries|city3=Harrison}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=39.024\n|exit=39\n|road=[[Old Mission State Park]]\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=40.096\n|exit=40\n|road=[[Cataldo, Idaho|Cataldo]]\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|county=Shoshone\n|cspan=18\n|location=Kingston\n|mile=43.016\n|exit=43\n|road=[[Image:Forest Route 9.svg|20px]]&nbsp;FR 9 \u2013 [[Kingston, Idaho|Kingston]], [[Thompson Pass (Idaho / Montana)|Thompson Pass]]\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=45.261\n|exit=45\n|road=[[Pinehurst, Idaho|Pinehurst]], [[Smelterville, Idaho|Smelterville]]\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=47.687\n|exit=48\n|road=[[Smelterville, Idaho|Smelterville]], [[Shoshone County Airport]]\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=Kellogg\n|lspan=3\n|mile=49.715\n|exit=49\n|road=Bunker Avenue&nbsp;\u2013 [[Silver Mountain (Idaho)|Silver Mountain]]\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=50.321\n|exit=50\n|road=Hill Street\n|notes=Eastbound exit and westbound entrance\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=50.551\n|exit=51\n|road=Division Street&nbsp;\u2013 [[Wardner, Idaho|Wardner]]\n|notes=No westbound entrance\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=54.186\n|exit=54\n|road=[[Big Creek, Idaho|Big Creek]]\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=Osburn\n|mile=57.036\n|exit=57\n|road={{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Osburn|dir1=east|city1=Osburn}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=59.553\n|exit=60\n|road={{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Silverton|dir1=west|city1=Silverton|city2=Osburn}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=Wallace\n|lspan=2\n|mile=60.990\n|exit=61\n|road={{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Wallace|dir1=east|name1=The Harry F. Magnuson Way|city1=Wallace}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|mile=61.948\n|exit=62\n|road={{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Wallace|dir1=west|name1=Bank Street / The Harry F. Magnuson Way|city1=Wallace|SH|4|dir2=east|name2=Burke Road|city2=Burke}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=64.270\n|exit=64\n|road=Golconda District\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=65.352\n|exit=65\n|road=Compressor District\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|location=none\n|mile=66.500\n|exit=66\n|road=[[Gold Creek, Idaho|Gold Creek]]\n|notes=Eastbound exit and entrance\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=67.353\n|exit=67\n|road=Morning District, [[West Mullan, Idaho|West Mullan]]\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=Mullan\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=68.100\n|exit=68\n|road={{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Mullan|dir1=east|city1=Mullan}}\n|notes=Eastbound exit and westbound entrance\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=68.908\n|exit=69\n|road={{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Mullan|dir1=west|city1=Mullan|city2=East Mullan}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=73.888\n|road={{Jct|state=MT|I|90|dir1=East|name1=[[Lookout Pass]]|city1=Missoula}}\n|notes=Continuation into Montana\n}}\n{{jctbtm|exit|keys=incomplete}}\n\n==Related routes==\n{{AttachedKML|display=title,inline}}\n* {{section link|Business routes of Interstate 90|Idaho}}\n* ''[[U.S. Route 10]]''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{state detail page browse|type=I|route=90|state=Idaho|stateafter=Montana|statebefore=Washington}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Interstate 90 In Idaho}}\n[[Category:Interstate 90| Idaho]]\n[[Category:Interstate Highways in Idaho|90]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Kootenai County, Idaho]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Shoshone County, Idaho]]\n", "text_old": "{{highway detail hatnote|Interstate 90}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=ID\n|type=I\n|route=90\n|alternate_name=Purple Heart Trail\n|map={{MapframeForObjects|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Interstate 90 in Idaho}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=I-90 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=73.888\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"milepoint log\">{{cite web|title=Milepoint Log Report|url=http://itd.idaho.gov/highways/milepointlog/logs/interState/I_90_MPLog.pdf|publisher=[[Idaho Transportation Department]]|accessdate=July 11, 2015|format=PDF|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713030426/http://itd.idaho.gov/highways/milepointlog/logs/interState/I_90_MPLog.pdf|archivedate=July 13, 2015}}</ref>\n|established=1957\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a={{Jct|state=WA|I|90}} at the [[Washington (state)|Washington]] state line\n|junction={{plainlist|\n*{{jct|state=ID|SH|41}} in [[Post Falls, Idaho|Post Falls]]\n*{{Jct|state=ID|US|95}} in [[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho|Coeur d'Alene]]\n*{{jct|state=ID|SH|97}} near [[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho|Coeur d'Alene]]\n*{{jct|state=ID|SH|3}} near [[Cataldo, Idaho|Cataldo]]\n*{{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Wallace|SH|4}} in [[Wallace, Idaho|Wallace]]\n}}\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b={{Jct|state=MT|I|90}} at the [[Montana]] state line\n|counties=[[Kootenai County, Idaho|Kootenai]], [[Shoshone County, Idaho|Shoshone]]\n|previous_type=US\n|previous_route=89\n|next_type=US\n|next_route=91\n}}\n\n'''Interstate&nbsp;90''' ('''I-90''') is a transcontinental [[Interstate Highway System|Interstate Highway]] that runs east\u2013west across the northern United States. Within the state of [[Idaho]], the freeway travels for {{convert|74|mi|km|0}} from the [[Washington (state)|Washington]] border near [[Spokane, Washington|Spokane]] to [[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho|Coeur d'Alene]] and the [[Idaho Panhandle|panhandle region]] at the north end of the state. After traveling through the [[Silver Valley (Idaho)|Silver Valley]] along the [[Coeur d'Alene River]] in the [[Bitterroot Range]], I-90 crosses into [[Montana]] at [[Lookout Pass]].\n\nI-90 was created by the federal government in 1957, following the general route of [[U.S. Route 10 in Idaho|U.S. Route 10]] (US&nbsp;10) and the mid-19th century [[Mullan Road]] constructed by the U.S. Army. The freeway was constructed in stages between 1960 and 1992.\n\n==Route description==\n\nInterstate&nbsp;90 enters Idaho at a crossing of the [[Spokane River]] in the community of [[State Line, Idaho|State Line]] in [[Kootenai County, Idaho|Kootenai County]], approximately {{convert|20|mi|km}} east of [[Spokane, Washington]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Geranios |first=Nicholas K. |date=January 8, 2011 |title=Idaho town to lottery winner: Please show yourself |url=http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sdut-idaho-town-to-lottery-winner-please-show-yourself-2011jan08-story.html |work=[[San Diego Union-Tribune]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=September 24, 2018}}</ref> The freeway travels northeast through the [[Rathdrum Prairie]] and into the outskirts of [[Post Falls, Idaho|Post Falls]], passing several retailers and a [[business park]] along the Spokane River. I-90 continues east along the river, paralleled to the south by the [[North Idaho Centennial Trail]] and a section of the [[BNSF Railway]], and passes near the eponymous [[Post Falls]] and the city's downtown, served by a signed [[business route]]. The freeway intersects [[Idaho State Highway 41|State Highway 41]] (SH-41) and continues through the city's eastern residential neighborhoods and passes the nearby town of [[Huetter, Idaho|Huetter]]. I-90 then reaches [[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho|Coeur d'Alene]], the largest city in northern Idaho, and intersects a business route and [[U.S. Route 95 in Idaho|US-95]], the state's main north\u2013south highway, near the [[Kootenai Medical Center]].<ref name=\"google\">{{google maps |title=Interstate 90 |url=https://www.google.com/maps/dir/47.696623,-117.0416018/47.4560707,-115.6953649/@47.5851041,-116.6479888,10z/data=!4m2!4m1!3e0 |accessdate=September 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe freeway travels around the north and east sides of central Coeur d'Alene, intersecting several local streets in the process, and turns southeast towards [[Fernan Lake]] and [[Lake Coeur d'Alene]] on the Spokane River. I-90 ascends Potlatch Hill and makes several stair-step turns to follow the northern shore of Lake Coeur d'Alene while traversing several forested hills. It passes {{convert|240|ft|m}} over a valley overlooking Bennett Bay on the [[Veterans Memorial Centennial Bridge]], a high concrete bridge that was completed in 1987.<ref>{{cite news |date=February 10, 2017 |title=Bennett Bay Bridge offers best of form and function |url=http://apps.itd.idaho.gov/Apps/MediaManagerMVC/transporter/2017/021017_Trans/021017_VaultBennettBayBr.html |work=The Transporter |publisher=Idaho Transportation Department |accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref> The freeway descends from the hills and travels southeasterly along Wolf Lodge Bay, passing [[Coeur d'Alene Parkway State Park]] and intersecting the northern terminus of the [[Lake Coeur d'Alene Scenic Byway]] ([[Idaho State Highway 97|SH-97]]) at the east end of the lake. I-90 continues east along Cedar Creek into the [[Coeur d'Alene Mountains]], part of a [[Coeur d'Alene National Forest|national forest]],<ref name=\"google\"/> and reaches [[Fourth of July Summit]] at an elevation of {{convert|3,173|ft}}.<ref name=\"Spokesman-Passes\">{{cite news |last=Prager |first=Mike |date=May 16, 2017 |title=Snow returns to the mountains, but warmer weather will arrive by the weekend |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2017/may/16/snow-returns-to-the-mountains-but-warmer-weather-w/ |work=The Spokesman-Review |accessdate=September 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:I-90IDWallace.jpg|thumb|Eastbound I-90 on the 1991 viaduct<br/>at [[Wallace, Idaho|Wallace]] in 2007]]\n\nFrom the summit, I-90 continues southeast along Fourth of July Canyon towards the [[Coeur d'Alene River]] valley and intersects [[Idaho State Highway 3|SH-3]] near [[Rose Lake, Idaho|Rose Lake]]. The freeway bends northward around a hill and travels east into the river valley, passing [[Cataldo, Idaho|Cataldo]] and the [[Old Mission State Park]], home to the state's oldest standing building.<ref>{{cite news |date=January 15, 2009 |title=Idaho to cut Cataldo Mission park funding |url=https://missoulian.com/lifestyles/recreation/idaho-to-cut-cataldo-mission-park-funding/article_46fb1220-378a-5f84-97ba-712bdf27938f.html |work=[[Missoulian]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref> In Cataldo, it also crosses the river and the [[Trail of the Coeur d'Alenes]], a major rail trail that follows the highway into the [[Bitterroot Range]].<ref name=\"Kitsap-Trail\">{{cite news |last=Blair Jr. |first=Seabury |date=September 25, 2007 |title=72 Miles of Idaho Fun |page=17 |work=[[Kitsap Sun]] |url=http://archive.kitsapsun.com/outdoors/72-miles-of-idaho-fun-ep-422743545-358852731.html |accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref> I-90 crosses into [[Shoshone County, Idaho|Shoshone County]], one of only two counties along the highway within Idaho,<ref>{{cite news |last=Dukes |first=Lucy |date=March 15, 2008 |title=Pick Of The Litter? |page=C1 |work=[[The Coeur d'Alene Press]]}}</ref> and continues along the north sides of [[Pinehurst, Idaho|Pinehurst]] and [[Smelterville, Idaho|Smelterville]], passing the [[Shoshone County Airport]] at the latter. The freeway travels southeasterly through [[Kellogg, Idaho|Kellogg]], passing the [[Silver Mountain Resort]] and its [[ski gondola]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Geranios |first=Nicholas K. |date=September 16, 2007 |title=Silver lining \u2014 Former Idaho mining town finds new life as swanky ski resort |work=Missoulian |agency=Associated Press |url=https://missoulian.com/business/silver-lining-former-idaho-mining-town-finds-new-life-as/article_accea8e1-564f-5aba-872e-febf04a65d09.html |accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref> and continues around the towns of [[Osburn, Idaho|Osburn]] and [[Silverton, Idaho|Silverton]] along the north bank of the [[South Fork Coeur d'Alene River]] at the bottom of the narrow [[Silver Valley (Idaho)|Silver Valley]].<ref name=\"google\"/> I-90 also intersects a set of business routes in Osburn and Silverton that loop back to the freeway.\n\nThe freeway turns east in the town of [[Wallace, Idaho|Wallace]], also served by its own business route, and travels to the north of downtown on an elevated viaduct cut into a nearby hill.<ref>{{cite news |last=Prager |first=Mike |date=May 3, 2010 |title=Wallace honoring savior |page=A8 |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2010/may/03/wallace-honoring-savior/ |work=The Spokesman-Review |accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref> At the east end of Wallace, I-90 intersects [[Idaho State Highway 4|SH-4]], which connects to the [[ghost town]] of [[Burke, Idaho|Burke]]. The highway continues along the south side of the river and Trail of the Coeur d'Alenes as it ascends further into the mountains and meanders around hills and gulches.<ref>{{cite news |last=Malgesini |first=Tammy |date=August 18, 2012 |title=Rich history of Wallace |work=[[East Oregonian]]}}</ref> The trail ends at the town of [[Mullan, Idaho|Mullan]],<ref name=\"Kitsap-Trail\"/> named for road-building U.S. Army captain [[John Mullan (road builder)|John Mullan]] and home to a business route,<ref name=\"AP-Mullan\">{{cite news |last=Geranios |first=Nicholas K. |date=June 15, 2003 |title=Little-Known Road Played Big Role in Conquest of the West |page=A28 |work=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |agency=Associated Press |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2003/jun/15/news/adna-mullan15 |accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref> and I-90 continues east along the [[Northern Pacific Trail]]. The freeway travels uphill from the river along a southern ridge and passes a [[scenic viewpoint]] commemorating the 1903 [[Willow Creek avalanche]].<ref>https://history.idaho.gov/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/Idaho-Highway-Historical-Marker-Guide.pdf</ref>{{cn|date=September 2018}} I-90 then turns south and leaves Idaho at [[Lookout Pass]], elevated {{convert|4,725|ft}} above sea level and located adjacent to the [[Lookout Pass Ski and Recreation Area]].<ref name=\"google\"/><ref name=\"Spokesman-Passes\"/> The freeway [[Interstate 90 in Montana|continues]] into [[Montana]] and travels through the cities of [[Butte, Montana|Butte]], [[Bozeman, Montana|Bozeman]], and [[Billings, Montana|Billings]].<ref>{{cite map |year=2016 |title=Montana Highway Map |publisher=[[Montana Department of Transportation]] |location=Helena, Montana |scale=Scale not given |url=https://mdt.mt.gov/travinfo/docs/2016-mt-highway-map.pdf |accessdate=September 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nI-90 is the only Interstate in [[Idaho Panhandle|northern Idaho]] and a major east\u2013west route,<ref name=\"map\">{{citation |title=Idaho Official Highway Map |publisher=[[Idaho Department of Transportation]] |year=2007 |edition=2007 |place=[[Boise, Idaho|Boise]], [[Idaho]]}}</ref> forming part of a transcontinental highway. At {{convert|74|mi|km}}, it is the second-shortest mainline Interstate in the state, after [[Interstate 86 (Idaho)|Interstate 86]], and the third-longest.{{cn|date=October 2018}} The entire highway was designated as the [[Purple Heart]] Trail by the state legislature in 2008.<ref>{{cite news |last=Russell |first=Betsy |date=August 12, 2014 |title=I-84 now officially Vietnam Veterans Memorial Highway |url=http://www.spokesman.com/blogs/boise/2014/aug/12/i-84-now-officially-vietnam-veterans-memorial-highway/ |work=[[The Spokesman-Review]] |accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Idaho Statues 40-513C: Designation of Purple Heart Trail |year=2008 |url=https://legislature.idaho.gov/statutesrules/idstat/title40/t40ch5/sect40-513c/ |publisher=[[Idaho Legislature]] |accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> The Idaho section of I-90 is maintained by the [[Idaho Transportation Department]] (ITD), which conducts an annual survey of traffic on certain highway segments that is expressed in terms of [[average annual daily traffic]] (AADT), a measure of traffic volume for any average day of the year. Traffic volumes on I-90 ranged from a minimum of 7,861 near Mullan and 60,729 in Huetter on an average day in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=ATR & WIM Data: Interstate 90 |url=https://apps.itd.idaho.gov/apps/roadwaydata/Maps/ATR_I90_list.html |publisher=Idaho Transportation Department |accessdate=September 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nInterstate 90 from Coeur d'Alene to Lookout Pass roughly follows the route of the [[Mullan Road]], constructed in 1859\u201360 by the U.S. Army and civilian volunteers led by captain [[John Mullan (road builder)|John Mullan]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Mccroskeyjeri Mccroskey |first=Jerry |date=June 4, 2005 |title=John Mullan created road with future travelers in mind |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2005/jun/04/john-mullan-created-road-with-future-travelers-in/ |work=The Spokesman-Review |accessdate=September 24, 2018}}</ref> Mullan received a series of appropriations from U.S. Congress from 1855 to 1860, totaling $230,000, to build the first engineered road west of the [[Mississippi River]] and connect [[Fort Walla Walla]] to [[Fort Benton, Montana|Fort Benton]].<ref name=\"AP-Mullan\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Kramer |first=Becky |date=July 4, 2005 |title=A road to remember |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2005/jul/04/a-road-to-remember/ |work=The Spokesman-Review |accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> The road also followed the [[Coeur d'Alene River]] and its south fork, which was long used by the [[Coeur d'Alene people]] to visit hunting grounds in modern-day [[Montana]].<ref name=\"Schwieterman\">{{cite book |last=Schwieterman |first=Joseph P. |year=2004 |title=When the Railroad Leaves Town: American Communities in the Age of Rail Line Abandonment |pages=124\u2013128 |publisher=[[Truman State University Press]] |location=Kirksville, Missouri |isbn=1-931112-13-4 |oclc=56968524 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kzk_m4P9Y6kC |via=Google Books |accessdate=October 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOther sections of I-90 were built over the [[Yellowstone Trail]] and [[U.S. Route 10 in Idaho|U.S. Route 10]],<ref name=ietlfwy>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Lc8zAAAAIBAJ&sjid=avcDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7087%2C4638462 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |agency=Associated Press |title=Idaho eyes twin-level freeway |date=December 18, 1963 |page=6 }}</ref> though some parts of I-90 were cut as new roadway.<ref name=nwrow57>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VPxXAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6PYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5498%2C155350 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |title=Idaho seeking funds to buy right of way for freeway route |date=February 1, 1957|page=a3}}</ref><ref name=displres>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kZ5YAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hvgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7073%2C4319199 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |agency=Associated Press |last=Leeright |first=Bob |title=Displaced residents add to cost of highways |date=July 31, 1971|page=5}}</ref> The link from Post Falls to the Washington state border was completed in 1972 at a cost of $1.1 million to upgrade the existing road and build a new bridge over the Spokane River.<ref name=frwncom>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CaJYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mfgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7161%2C2273838 |work=Spokane Daily Chronicle |last=Evarts |first=J. Neal|title=Freeway work nears completion |date=October 9, 1972 |page=1 |via=Google News Archive |accessdate=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe small town of [[Wallace, Idaho|Wallace]] in the Silver Valley still prides itself on having what was the last stoplight on I-90. Its downtown has many historical buildings, which would have been wiped out by the original planned route of the freeway,<ref name=wallccexp>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vLwzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=L_gDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4669%2C2078459 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |title=Plans for Interstate 90 explained to Wallace CC |date=January 23, 1970 |page=3 }}</ref><ref name=wcsi90shf>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=16hYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tvgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4551%2C1134583 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |title=Wallace Chamber seeks I-90 shift |date=January 18, 1973 |page=b3 }}</ref> so in 1976, city leaders had the downtown placed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=wfwhrgo>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=W_dLAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ne0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6862%2C2634191 |newspaper=Spokesman-Review |location=Spokane, Washington |agency=Associated Press |title=Wallace freeway hearing ordered by federal judge|date=July 23, 1976|page=13}}</ref><ref name=sinchst>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=d0FYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KvkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4800%2C2425121 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |title=I-90 study includes historic site survey |date=January 10, 1980 |page=10 }}</ref><ref name=wfw12yrovd>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=D1VOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xu4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=6844%2C4794390 |newspaper=Spokesman-Review |location=Spokane, Washington |last=Collin|first=Matthew |title=Wallace freeway 12 years overdue |date=January 26, 1981 |page=6 }}</ref> Alternatives discussed in 1963 included tunnels and twin levels.<ref name=ietlfwy/><ref name=fwyaltrv>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=r1ZOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=FfkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4581%2C2716011 |newspaper=Spokane Daily Chronicle |location=Washington |agency=Associated Press |title=Freeway alternatives reviewed for Wallace |date=October 25, 1978 |page=5 }}</ref>\n\nAs a result, the federal government was forced at great expense to reroute the freeway to the northern edge of downtown and elevate it. Work on that section was resumed in 1984,<ref name=wbwtst>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=YFhWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=--4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=3163%2C1053173|newspaper=Spokesman-Review |location=Spokane, Washington |last=Bond |first=Dave |title=Wallace bypass work to start |date=July 18, 1984 |page=1}}</ref> and it opened in September 1991.<ref name=\"itd\">[http://itd.idaho.gov/50.Years/I-50_I-90.html Idaho Transportation Department] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060926064753/http://itd.idaho.gov/50.Years/I-50_I-90.html |date=September 26, 2006 }}</ref> A bicycle path is routed beneath part of that segment. Before the move to the viaduct, I-90 went from a freeway at the western edge of Wallace, then turned to surface streets and followed the main arterial as U.S. Route 10 through town, which included the last stoplight on I-90 between Seattle and Boston.<ref name=hsi90riotn>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=JRBWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=S-IDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5671%2C3457563 |newspaper=Eugene Register-Guard |location=Oregon |agency=Associated Press |title=He stalled Interstate 90 right in the middle of town |date=February 13, 1981|page=15F}}</ref> Upon reaching the eastern edge of the town it became a limited access divided highway once again.<ref name=lstplt>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=tJtTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=c4YDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7050%2C6073186 |newspaper=The Bulletin |location=Bend, Oregon |agency=Associated Press |title=Lone stoplight on Interstate 90 to pass by after new bypass |date=September 8, 1991 |page=A9 }}</ref>\n\nThe interstate also was routed along [[Lake Coeur d'Alene]] as a surface street before the [[Veterans Memorial Centennial Bridge]] was completed in 1992, traveling further above the lake.<ref name=\"Spokesman-50\">{{cite news |last=Cannata |first=Amy |date=September 10, 2006 |title=Freeway at 50 |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2006/sep/10/freeway-at-50/ |work=Spokesman-Review |accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==Exit list==\n{{Jcttop|exit|length_ref=<ref name=\"milepoint log\"/>|exit_ref=<ref name=\"milepoint log\"/>}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|county=Kootenai\n|cspan=18\n|location=none\n|mile=0.000\n|road={{Jct|state=WA|I|90|dir1=West|city1=Spokane}}\n|notes=Continuation into Washington\n}}\n{{anchor|Spokane River Bridge}}\n{{Jctbridge|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=0.000\n|mile2=0.098\n|bridge=Bridge over [[Spokane River]]\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=Post Falls\n|lspan=5\n|mile=1.160\n|exit=1\n|road=Beck Road (via Pointe Parkway)\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|mile=2.080\n|exit=2\n|road=Pleasant View Road\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|mile=4.632\n|exit=5\n|road={{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Post Falls|dir1=east|name1=Spokane Street|location1=[[City Center (Post Falls, Idaho)|City Center]]}}\n|notes=Exit is just east of northernmost point on I-90\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|type=incomplete\n|mile=5.450\n|exit=6\n|road={{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Post Falls|dir1=west|name1=Seltice Way / 4th Avenue|location1=[[City Center (Post Falls, Idaho)|City Center]]}}\n|notes=Westbound exit and eastbound entrance\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|mile=7.128\n|exit=7\n|road={{jct|state=ID|SH|41|dir1=north|city1=Rathdrum|city2=Spirit Lake}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=Coeur d'Alene\n|lspan=5\n|mile=11.290\n|exit=11\n|road={{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Coeur d'Alene|dir1=east|name1=Northwest Boulevard|location1=[[City Center (Coeur d'Alene, Idaho)|City Center]]}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|mile=12.040\n|exit=12\n|road={{jct|state=ID|US|95|city1=Sandpoint|city2=Moscow|name1=Lincoln Way|location3=[[Silverwood Theme Park|Silverwood]]|location4=[[British Columbia Highway 95|Canada]]}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|mile=12.560\n|exit=13\n|road=4th Street\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|mile=13.560\n|exit=14\n|road=15th Street\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|mile=14.780\n|exit=15\n|road={{jct|state=ID|BL|90|dab1=Coeur d'Alene|dir1=west|name1=Sherman Avenue|city1=Fernan|location1=[[City Center (Coeur d'Alene, Idaho)|City Center]]}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=16.882\n|exit=17\n|road=Mullan Trail Road\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=22.063\n|exit=22\n|road={{jct|state=ID|SH|97|dir1=south|city1=Harrison|city2=St. Maries}}\n}}\n{{IDint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=28.380\n|exit=28\n